# Cyrius Field Notes — Kernel Experiences
# Lessons from building and hardening the AGNOS kernel in Cyrius.

[[entries]]
name = "the_143kb_lie"
description = "How 14 buffer overflows made a kernel look smaller than it was — the AGNOS v1.11.0 to v1.22.0 hardening story"
category = "cyrius"
---
THE 143KB LIE

AGNOS kernel v1.11.0 was 143KB. It booted, ran 10 benchmarks, passed every CI
check, served TCP connections, read FAT16 filesystems, and dropped you into an
interactive shell with 18 commands. It looked correct.

It was riddled with buffer overflows.

Three audit passes — each one finding critical bugs the previous one missed —
revealed 14 undersized buffers. The pattern was always the same: `var buf[N]`
where N was the number of ENTRIES, not the number of BYTES. Cyrius allocates
bytes. If each entry is 32 bytes and you want 16 entries, you need var buf[512].
The kernel had var buf[16].

THE HIGHLIGHTS:

  proc_table[336]    — fits 2 procs (168B each), allowed 16. Overflow: 2352 bytes.
  idt[512]           — fits 32 vectors (16B each), needs 256. Overflow: 3584 bytes.
  vfs_table[128]     — fits 4 file descriptors (32B each), used 32. Overflow: 864 bytes.
  tcp_conns[80]      — fits 1 connection (80B each), allowed 8. Overflow: 560 bytes.
  sc_normal[16]      — fits 16 scancode entries (1B each), indexed by 128. Overflow: 112 bytes.
  sh_buf[16]         — 16 bytes for a shell command buffer that accepted 126 chars.
  gdt[8]             — 8 bytes for a 56-byte Global Descriptor Table.
  tss[16]            — 16 bytes for a 104-byte Task State Segment.

The kernel worked because Cyrius lays out globals sequentially and the overflowed
data landed in adjacent variables that happened to tolerate being overwritten.
The IDT was overwriting the ISR stub, the GDT pointer, and part of the TSS — but
those were initialized later in the boot sequence, so the overwrite was invisible.
The proc_table was overwriting the signal arrays — but signals weren't used during
the benchmarks that validated correctness.

WHAT IT TOOK TO FIND THEM:

Pass 1: Found proc_table, vfs_create_pipe leak, signal bounds, ELF loader failures.
        The obvious stuff. Fixed 19 items.

Pass 2: Found sh_buf, tcp_conns, proc_create_address_space rollback.
        Harder to spot — required tracing computed indices through function calls.

Pass 3: The systematic one. For every `var name[N]`, computed max access offset
        and compared to N. Found gdt, tss, idt, kb_isr, sc_normal, sc_shifted,
        vfs_table, dev_table, pci_devs. The big ones.

THE COST OF CORRECTNESS:

  Before: 143KB, "all tests pass", benchmarks look great
  After:  220KB, all tests still pass, benchmarks within noise
  Final:  260KB, 31 security fixes, ACPI+IOMMU, KPTI, Spectre v2, stack canaries

The binary grew 82% from first lie to final truth. The 220KB was the buffer
overflow fix. The jump to 260KB was a full security audit (v1.22.0): 31 fixes
across 5 passes, two new subsystems (ACPI table parsing + VT-d IOMMU), per-CPU
TSS, dual page tables for KPTI, IBRS for Spectre v2, stack canaries in critical
functions, spinlocked PMM, guard pages below every user stack, and NX bits on
data pages. That's the honest size of a kernel with 35 subsystems, 26 syscalls,
TCP/IP, FAT16, VirtIO, SMP, an ELF loader, and an interactive shell — one that
actually validates its inputs and restricts DMA.

Benchmark impact was negligible. Heap_32B actually got faster (1,460 → 1,338
cycles) because the slab allocator's free lists were no longer corrupted by
adjacent overflows. The I/O paths slowed ~15% from larger data segment cache
pressure — the cost of having correctly sized interrupt descriptor tables.

LESSON:

In Cyrius, `var buf[N]` is N bytes. Not N entries. Not N elements. Bytes.
Every buffer declaration is a contract: "I need exactly this many bytes."
Break the contract and everything works until it doesn't. The kernel will
boot, the tests will pass, the benchmarks will look good. But the data
structures are eating each other alive, and the only sign is a binary
that's suspiciously small.

260KB for a hardened kernel is hard to beat. 143KB was too good to be true —
and it was.

[[entries]]
name = "the_road_to_iron"
description = "Three weeks, eight iron attempts, two GRUB walls, one architectural pivot to a sovereign UEFI bootloader — the walk from QEMU-clean to first kernel-on-NUC instruction"
category = "cyrius"
---
THE ROAD TO IRON

QEMU is a liar. Not on purpose, and not always — but reliably enough that
"boots clean in QEMU" is at best a necessary condition for boot-on-iron,
never a sufficient one. The AGNOS kernel had been booting clean in QEMU
for months when we started flashing it to a USB stick and pointing the
NUC AMD at it on 2026-05-12. Eight attempts later, we have a kernel
that gets through `gdt_init`, walks into `tss_init`, and triple-faults
on a single wrong byte in an inline asm block. Between those two states
are five real walls, one wrong diagnostic, and one fairly violent
architectural pivot. Here's the shape.

THE FIRST WALL — THE DUMBEST, IN THE BEST WAY

GRUB rejected the kernel with `grub_elf32_get_shnum:227: invalid section
header table offset in e_shoff`. Cyrius's ELF emitter had been writing
program-headers-only ELFs — valid for Linux's `execve` (which only
consumes program headers) and therefore valid in QEMU's `-kernel` mode
(which uses a Linux-style loader). GRUB's ELF parser is stricter and
rejects anything with `e_shoff = 0`. Fix: a 250-line patch to
`cyrius/src/backend/x86/fixup.cyr` to emit five real section headers
(NULL + .text + .rodata + .bss + .shstrtab). Shipped as cyrius 5.11.29.
Mirrored to the aarch64 emitter and the user-binary ELF64 linker as
5.11.30 and 5.11.31. Kernel grew 232 bytes. Cost: a coffee.

THE SECOND WALL — GRUB SAYS NO VIDEO

`grub_video_set_mode: no suitable video mode found.` On UEFI hardware
that exposes only GOP/UGA — which is every modern board — GRUB needs
`insmod all_video` and `insmod efi_gop` loaded, and the grub.cfg needs
`set gfxpayload=text` because AGNOS uses VGA text + serial, not a
framebuffer console. One commit to `scripts/install-usb.sh`, USB
re-provisioned. Done in twenty minutes.

THE THIRD WALL — GRUB FORGOT TO LEAVE LONG MODE

After fixing the video probe: `WARNING: no console will be available to
OS` and then a reset. Attempt 4 retried with a CPUID-gated CR4 fix that
turned out to be a no-op on Zen silicon (predicted before the run,
confirmed after). Same warning, same reset. Bare retry was exhausted;
we needed visibility into kernel-side execution and didn't have it.

Reading GRUB source while not boot-attempting turned out to be the
load-bearing diagnostic. GRUB-EFI on x86_64 invokes
`grub_relocator64_efi_boot`, which calls `grub_relocator64_efi_start` —
a 64-bit-state stub that does `jmp *jump_addr(%rip)` without `cli`,
without `lgdt`, without clearing `CR0.PG`, `CR4.PAE`, or `EFER.LME`.
**GRUB-EFI hands off with the CPU still in 64-bit long mode.** Our
ELF32 kernel's 32-bit-protected-mode instructions decoded as garbage
64-bit opcodes when fetched in long mode; the kernel triple-faulted on
instruction #1. Linux distros don't trip this because they boot via
`linuxefi`, not multiboot — entirely different relocator. The
multiboot1 + UEFI path is dead for any kernel that isn't already a
64-bit ELF with a multiboot2 header.

Pivot to Path A: ELF64 + multiboot2 + `MULTIBOOT_HEADER_TAG_ENTRY_ADDRESS_EFI64`.
Cyrius 5.11.43 landed `EMITELF64_KERNEL`. Agnos shim rewrote the entry
sequence for long-mode-inherited state. Build verified in QEMU `-kernel`.
~6 hours. Felt like we'd cleared it.

THE FOURTH WALL — GRUB WRITES TO ITS OWN .TEXT

Then the QEMU OVMF gate — same firmware path the iron uses, just
emulated. `WARNING: no console will be available to OS` followed by:

  X64 Exception 0E (#PF — Page Fault), ErrorCode 0x3 (P=1 W=1)
  RIP 0xBD3D22E (firmware-loaded memory)
  RAX = 0x36D76289 (multiboot2 magic — GRUB had prepared the handoff)

Protection violation on a write inside `grub_relocator64_efi_boot`.
`objdump` + `readelf -r` on `/usr/lib/grub/x86_64-efi/relocator.mod`
made the design explicit: `grub_relocator64_efi_boot` issues six
`movabs %rax, <addr_inside_the_stub>` writes — **patching kernel
register state directly into the stub's bytecode** before jumping.
Six writes to its own `.text`. OVMF 2024+ enforces strict-W^X on PE
`.text` pages. The writes fault.

This was the wall that killed Path A. The multiboot2 + GRUB-EFI
relocator path is genuinely broken under modern firmware, and Linux
distros don't see it because they don't use it. We searched Red Hat
Bugzilla and the GRUB lists — no upstream report names
`grub_relocator64_efi_boot` + W^X by that combination. We're a fresh
datapoint on a death the rest of the industry already arranged around.
Fedora 42's strict-NX change in January 2025 was the explicit cliff;
we hit it 16 months later.

THE PIVOT — GNOBOOT

The pivot to Path C — sovereign UEFI bootloader, no GRUB on the chain —
happened over the next 8 hours on 2026-05-13. Path C was always the
long-term destination per the bootloader roadmap; the W^X wall just
brought the timeline forward to "now." Cyrius gained UEFI Application
emit (5.11.49). A new repo, `gnoboot`, came up: PE32+ UEFI binary,
Cyrius-native, ~35KB final size. Twelve verification gates, eleven
cleared in one session: ConOut banner, `HandleProtocol(LoadedImage)`,
`SimpleFileSystemProtocol`, open `\boot\agnos`, parse ELF64 program
headers, `AllocatePages` at 0x100000, load 245KB segment, `GetMemoryMap`,
build sovereign 80-byte boot-info struct (magic `0x41474E4F = 'AGNO'`),
call `ExitBootServices`, `mov rdi, &boot_info; mov eax, 0x1000A8;
jmp rax`. Agnos shim swap from MBI parse to sovereign-struct read, six
edits in the agnos repo. End-to-end QEMU OVMF: kernel reaches
`Activating scheduler...`. Gnoboot 0.1.0 cut, agnos 1.30.0 cut. Ready
for iron.

THE FIFTH AND SIXTH WALLS — UEFI ALLOCATEPAGES DOESN'T ZERO, AND
                              EFILOADERDATA IS NX

Iron Attempt 5: gnoboot reached step 7, kernel triple-faulted post-jump,
machine reset. Bit-identical to a kernel that never ran. Two
high-confidence hypotheses for the QEMU-OVMF / iron divergence:

1. **BSS gap not zeroed.** UEFI 2.x § 7.2 says `AllocatePages` returns
   undefined memory contents. QEMU OVMF happens to return zeroes; real
   firmware leaves POST/EFI scratch. Kernel `.bss` globals read garbage
   on iron, triple-fault at first reference.
2. **EfiLoaderData vs EfiLoaderCode.** Strict-W^X firmware NX-marks
   LoaderData pages. Jumping into one #PFs, IDT absent, triple-faults.
   OVMF runs from LoaderData regardless.

Both fixes shipped in Attempt 6. **No improvement.** Identical reset
cadence. Two highest-confidence hypotheses ruled out by negation. The
remaining hypotheses — Zen page-table W^X, GDT divergence, CR0/CR4/EFER
divergence including CET shadow stack — all required visibility into
kernel-side execution that we didn't have.

THE VISUAL CANARY — AMBIGUOUS SIGNAL

Attempt 7 added a visual canary: gnoboot located GOP pre-EBS, captured
`fb_phys/pitch/width/height/pixel_format` into the boot-info struct
(struct grew 80 → 112 bytes, version 1 → 2). Kernel boot-shim's first
26 bytes read `[rdi+0x48]`, and if non-zero, painted 256 white pixels
at top-left of screen. If we see a stripe, kernel executed at least one
instruction. If we don't, the failure is upstream of instruction #1.
**No stripe.** Reset. The canary's null-check meant we couldn't
distinguish Case A (`fb_phys == 0`, kernel ran invisibly) from Case B
(`jmp rax` never landed). We had ambiguous signal.

THE SERIAL CABLE THAT WASN'T

Across Attempts 4, 5, 6, and 7 we'd been recommending a USB-to-TTL
serial cable on the NUC's COM1 header as the next diagnostic. The
recommendation was structurally wrong. **The dev environment IS the
iron target** — single Beelink SER, no second host. A serial cable
needs another machine to read the wire. The right channel was always
something that survives a triple-fault reset on the same machine. CMOS
scratch RAM, UEFI NVRAM variables, raw disk sectors. We'd recommended
the wrong diagnostic three attempts running because we hadn't
internalized the dev-setup constraint. A memory pin records it now so
the next agent doesn't repeat it.

THE CMOS UNLOCK

Attempt 8 shipped the CMOS persistent boot log. Six 8-byte writes in
the kernel's boot-shim ELF64 asm block, each
`mov al, idx; out 0x70, al; mov al, val; out 0x71, al`. Slot map:
`CMOS[0x50]` = highest kernel checkpoint, `CMOS[0x51]` = `0xAB` magic
(kernel ran), `CMOS[0x52]` = gnoboot pre-jump checkpoint, `CMOS[0x53]` =
`0xCD` magic (gnoboot ran). Slots 0x50-0x7F because the archaemenid BIOS
writes 0x42-0x44 every cold boot. After the iron reset, a Cyrius binary
reads CMOS back through the bare-metal port-IO path: `/dev/nvram` is
dead on this BIOS (checksum mismatch), so the Linux driver couldn't
help us.

Verdict: gnoboot magic `0xCD`, gnoboot checkpoint `5` (all the way
through). Kernel magic `0xAB` (kernel ran). Kernel checkpoint `0x81`.
**`0x81` is "gdt_init returned, about to call tss_init."** `0x82` is
"tss_init returned." We didn't reach `0x82`. The fault is inside
`tss_init_cpu(0)`. First time in eight attempts we had a clean
bisection signal from iron, with no second host.

THE [RBP-0x08] TRAP

Reading `kernel/arch/x86_64/gdt.cyr`: the `ltr` asm block read
`[rbp-0x08]` and called it `selector`. Per Cyrius's frame convention
(documented in `ring3.cyr:25` — *"params at rbp-0x08, -0x10, -0x18;
new locals start at rbp-0x20"*), `[rbp-0x08]` in
`tss_init_cpu(cpu_id)` is the **parameter cpu_id**, not the local
`selector`. For the BSP, `cpu_id == 0`. So `ltr 0` loads the null TSS
descriptor → #GP → IDT not yet installed (`idt_init` is the very next
call) → triple fault → reset.

Fix: drop the `mov rax, [rbp-0x08]`, rely on Cyrius leaving `selector`
in `rax` from the assignment (same pattern `gdt_init` uses for `lgdt
[rax]` two functions up). Net: −4 instruction bytes. A second latent
bug surfaced by code-reading after the slot fix — `var gdt[56]` was
sized for the original 1-TSS layout but `gdt_init` writes through
offset 96, stomping `boot_info_ptr` in BSS. Resized to `var gdt[104]`.
Attempt 9 build sits at `build/agnos`, ready to flash.

HOW OTHERS DO IT

The reframe that took three weeks to earn:

Linux runs the kernel as a PE/COFF binary with an EFI stub linked in
(`drivers/firmware/efi/libstub/x86-stub.c`). The stub locates GOP,
captures the memory map, calls `ExitBootServices`, builds its own page
tables, jumps to the decompressor. FreeBSD's `loader.efi` does the
same shape with a separate binary, then jumps to the kernel with a
`modinfo` blob. OpenBSD's `efiboot/BOOTX64.EFI` does the same with
`boot_args`. Windows's `winload.efi` does the same with
`LOADER_PARAMETER_BLOCK` in RCX. Limine — the hobbyist reference
design — does the same with a request/response table embedded in the
kernel ELF. Every modern UEFI boot path on x86_64 is *some* variant
of: load PE binary → that PE locates GOP/memmap/RSDP → call EBS →
jump to kernel with a struct.

**Path C is that pattern.** The flat 112-byte struct in RDI is
BOOTBOOT-style. The Cyrius toolchain emitting PE/COFF is genuinely
new; the architecture is 10+ years old and converged-on. The Linux
EFI Handover Protocol is officially deprecated upstream as of v6.7
(late 2023). GRUB-multiboot2-EFI is the outlier the industry has been
quietly walking away from since 2023. AGNOS hit the cliff because OVMF
2024+ is strict-NX and `grub_relocator64_efi_boot`'s self-patching
`.text` is exactly the pattern strict-W^X kills.

(Full comparison with citations:
`agnosticos/docs/development/uefi-boot-prior-art.md`.)

WHAT THE WALK COST

  Attempts 1-4 + diagnoses:     ~30h iron testing + GRUB source review
  Path A scaffold (5.11.43):    ~6h cyrius + agnos shim ELF64 rewrite
  Path C scaffold (gnoboot):    ~8h cyrius UEFI emit + new repo + 11 verification gates
  Attempts 5-8 + slot-trap fix: ~16h BSS zero, EfiLoaderCode, canary,
                                CMOS bisector, gdt.cyr fix, gdt[104] resize
  Elapsed wall time:            3 weeks
  Effective engineering time:   ~60 hours

  Cyrius patches the walk needed:
    5.11.29  ELF section headers (x86 kernel emit)
    5.11.30  ELF section headers (aarch64 mirror)
    5.11.31  ELF section headers (cyrld user-binary linker)
    5.11.43  EMITELF64_KERNEL + multiboot2 + EFI64 entry tag
    5.11.49  UEFI Application emit mode (PE32+, NX_COMPAT, .reloc)
    5.11.52  fn efi_main(handle, st) convention + entry-save bug
    5.11.53  entry-save REX prefix hotfix
    5.11.54  LSP find_cc5 latest-symlink fallback (gnoboot LSP unblock)
    5.11.59  current pin (DCE-aware reachability filter cross-arch;
             diagnostic-surface polish via iron-boot papercut 4-slot
             arc .56-.59 — see retros/v511x.cyml)

  Kernel size across the walk:
    1.29.0 (pre-iron):    250704 bytes
    1.30.0 (gnoboot):     251040 bytes
    1.30.0 + canary:      251072 bytes
    1.30.0 + CMOS:        251232 bytes
    1.30.0 + slot fix:    251616 bytes (today)

LESSONS

QEMU is a liar. `qemu-system-x86_64 -kernel -cpu max` boots through a
Linux-style loader and bypasses everything GRUB-EFI does to your
registers. `-bios OVMF` is closer, but OVMF defaults are looser than
current iron firmware on NX. *Every QEMU "PASS" is a hypothesis test,
not a verdict.*

GRUB-EFI x86_64 doesn't exit long mode. If your kernel is ELF32, the
path is dead. Don't argue with it.

GRUB-EFI's multiboot2 relocator patches its own `.text`. Under
strict-W^X UEFI, this faults. Linux doesn't trip this because Linux
uses `linuxefi`, not multiboot. You will.

UEFI's `AllocatePages` returns undefined memory. Zero the BSS gap
yourself. QEMU OVMF happens to return zeroes; real firmware doesn't.

Strict-W^X firmware NX-marks `EfiLoaderData`. If you're allocating
pages you plan to jump into, ask for `EfiLoaderCode`.

The right diagnostic channel depends on your dev setup. We recommended
a serial cable for three attempts running, then realized we'd been
recommending the wrong tool for our hardware (single-machine dev = no
second host to read the wire). CMOS scratch RAM survives a triple-fault
reset on the same machine and the Cyrius `read-boot-log` binary reads
it back without needing the kernel nvram driver (which is dead on this
BIOS anyway).

Cyrius asm blocks that reference `[rbp-N]` are positional and
unforgiving. The convention is documented in `ring3.cyr:25` and worth
re-reading before writing a third asm-block-with-named-offset in 2026.

Most importantly: **what looks novel from inside the work usually
isn't.** AGNOS Path C is the same architectural shape as Linux's EFI
stub, FreeBSD's `loader.efi`, OpenBSD's `BOOTX64.EFI`, Windows's
`winload.efi`, and Limine's `BOOTX64.EFI`. The Cyrius toolchain emitting
PE/COFF is the novel piece; the architecture is 10+ years old and
converged-on. The walk to iron was hard because we discovered the
walls in the wrong order, not because the destination was unusual.

Attempt 9 is the next data point. Whatever it shows, the next wall
won't be in GRUB.

[[entries]]
name = "shell_on_iron"
description = "Attempts 9 through 29: how a kernel that compiled, booted in QEMU, and crashed on iron walked itself, repair-letter by repair-letter, to a visible shell prompt on a NUC AMD framebuffer"
category = "cyrius"
---
SHELL ON IRON

The first part of this story is "the_road_to_iron" — three weeks, eight
attempts, two GRUB walls, one architectural pivot, ending with Attempt 9
sitting at the workbench ready to flash. Repair (C) had pushed all 15
GPRs across context switches instead of the 9-caller-saved subset that
had been leaking rbx/rbp/r12-r15 between procs every tick. The kernel
compiled clean. The closed-beta gate — CP 0x11 MAGENTA — was four iron
attempts away.

Twenty-one attempts and seventeen repair letters later, the kernel
booted to a typeable shell prompt on the framebuffer. The keyboard
didn't work yet — but the shell was there, full kernel init log
rendering coherently above it, every checkpoint past closed-beta gate
held. Here's the shape of those twenty-one attempts.

THE QEMU LIE — IN BOTH DIRECTIONS

"QEMU is a liar" was the headline lesson from the first part. The
second part taught us the corollary: *QEMU lies in BOTH directions*.
A bug present in QEMU may be absent on iron, and a bug absent in QEMU
may be present on iron. Attempts 9 through 14 chased a scheduler hang
that reproduced consistently under `gnoboot + OVMF + qemu-system-x86_64
-cpu max` and looked architecturally serious — the kernel scheduler
appeared to starve `proc 0` (the idle task) after ~10 timer ticks. We
ran static walkthroughs of `sched_next` and `do_context_switch` after
Repair (A) (unconditional state-ready post-save) and Repair (B)
(`sched_next` fallback to proc 0); both should have worked; neither
did. Iron, when it finally booted past Repair (C), didn't reproduce
the hang at all. The QEMU stall was real — but specific to the
gnoboot+OVMF inherited-mapping edge case (page tables at fixed
physical `0x1000/0x2000/0x3000`, valid under the multiboot1 boot-shim's
seeded tables, not under UEFI). Iron firmware sets up mappings
differently and stepped through cleanly.

If we'd insisted on fixing the QEMU-visible bug before flashing, we'd
have walked into a real Repair (Q) that doesn't exist. "QEMU PASS" is
a hypothesis, not a verdict. "QEMU FAIL" is a hypothesis too.

REPAIR (C) — STATIC WALKTHROUGH IS HOW YOU FIND THE NEXT BUG

The pattern that crystallized at Repair (C) and held the rest of the
arc: when a fix lands, the kernel rebuilds clean, the next iron burn
hits the SAME trap stage — STOP and do a static code-walk of the
should-have-worked path. The bug isn't where you patched; the bug is
upstream of where you patched, or it's a parallel hazard the patch
didn't address.

Repair (A) + Repair (B) "should have" re-enabled proc 0 in the
scheduler rotation. Iron hit CP 0x23 anyway. Static walkthrough of
`pic.cyr`'s `timer_isr_build` showed an in-source comment claiming
"works on real hardware" — a prediction, never measured. The ISR
pushed 9 caller-saved GPRs but `proc_save_context` and
`proc_restore_context` operated on 15. rbx, rbp, r12-r15 leaked
between processes across every context switch. When proc 0 finally
re-ran, its `[rbp - N]` access to `idle_count` read test_proc_b's
stack (rbp pointing into stack_b at 0x820000+). No progress past
CP 0x23 because *the wrong stack was being read.*

Fix: push all 15 GPRs. Add 6 callee-saved load/store pairs in
proc_save_context/restore. Shift hardware-frame offsets +48. Build
grew 1,232 bytes. `timer_isr[]` buffer hit 63 of 64 bytes — one
byte headroom; future ISR additions must bump the buffer first.

CLOSED-BETA GATE — ATTEMPT 16

Attempt 16 hit CP 0x11 MAGENTA on iron. Closed-beta gate held. The
kernel completed: GDT → TSS → IDT → APIC → timer → SMP → keyboard ISR
→ paging → PMM → KASLR → heap → ACPI → PCI → VFS → SYSCALL → stack
canary → test procs → scheduler armed → idle loop survived → userland
exec → kybernet-launch. Three weeks of work hit its milestone gate
exactly where the spec said it should.

We celebrated for about ten minutes.

THE MEM-ISO RABBIT HOLE — ELEVEN ATTEMPTS, NINE REPAIRS, ALL DELETED

The kernel had a memory-isolation test block in `main.cyr:640-660`
that exercised the page-table dance for per-process address spaces:
SMAP brackets, CR3 swap to AS1, write/read round-trip, CR3 swap to
AS2, repeat, CR3 swap back to kernel. It worked under QEMU. On iron
it pegged kcp at 0x19 (the first cp_fb call after the block's exit)
across multiple cold burns.

Attempts 17-27 — eleven iron attempts, repair letters F through N —
walked a bisector ladder that progressively narrowed the death window
from "21 lines" to "one function" to "first MMIO write inside cp_fb
with fb_phys = 0 in hand." Repair (J) stamped PMM allocations to
CMOS slots 0x56-0x61. Repair (K) added 7 PML4 health stamps at
[0x62..0x68]. Repair (M) added 4 bisector stamps inside cp_fb itself.
Repair (N) added 6 more port-IO stamps and a cmos_stamp_fb_phys
helper. Every stamp fired exactly where it was supposed to. Every
stamp said the kernel was correct.

The bug looked like a non-deterministic gnoboot↔kernel handoff with
3-way visual asymmetry (cold-boot-with-USB-switchover, BIOS save-exit,
fault-reset all produced different states). It wasn't.

The premise was wrong. The mem-iso block was post-MVP work that had
been added to validate per-process address spaces — a feature not on
the closed-beta MVP boot path. The bug was real (fb_phys = 0 at the
moment cp_fb ran because the CR3 dance happened to disrupt the
boot_info mapping for one instant) but it was guarding a CAPABILITY
the MVP didn't need.

The fix was Repair (O): delete the 303 lines. The justification was
sitting on disk the entire time — `agnosticos/docs/development/
uefi-boot-prior-art.md` had flagged this code path as "post-MVP" in
the original Path-C scoping, two weeks before the bisector ladder
even started. We had walked past that justification at least four
times across the eleven attempts. We just didn't grep for it.

The premise-audit gate codified after this episode: **if a single
bug consumes 3+ diagnostic rounds without resolving, STOP and grep
the development docs for prior research on that code path.** The
mem-iso block deletion was prefigured in writing on disk. We chose
to instrument instead of grep, eleven times in a row.

A memory pin (`feedback_known_knowledge_first.md`) records the
discipline now. The next agent who finds themselves on bisector
round four checks the docs first.

MVP BOOT SPINE ALIVE ON IRON — ATTEMPT 28

Repair (O) plus a one-line follow-up (`sh_cmd_bench()` → `kybernet()`
at `main.cyr:415` to make the shell dispatch tree reachable) landed
in Attempt 28. The kernel completed its full init spine end-to-end
on archaemenid: every CMOS checkpoint painted, every kprintln
rendered, kybernet launched, shell entered, `arch_halt()` reached
as designed. Photo recorded — eight months of design and three
weeks of bring-up, one screen of green text.

The next surprise: the "MVP-to-typeable-shell gap" we'd planned to
close had two of three items already implemented. `fb_console.cyr`
had shipped an 8×8 CGA font and `fb_putc`/`fb_print`/`fb_println`
weeks earlier. `kprint.cyr` had been mirroring all output to serial
+ fb since the start of the cycle. Only the USB-keyboard input gap
was a real gap. Lesson: before planning a closing-the-gap-to-X arc,
grep for each gap to verify it's a gap. Two-thirds of a planned arc
was scaffolding around features that already worked.

REPAIR (P) — NON-ZERO GVAR INIT NOT HONORED

Attempt 29 burned a kernel that had reached kybernet (CMOS kcp=0x15
MAGENTA, no fault) but rendered the visual ladder with the cp_fb
cells in rows 1-2 wiped while row-9 yellows survived, and the
`agnos>` prompt was invisible. Pattern decoded to a single bug at
three module-scope coordinates:

  var FB_CONSOLE_Y0 = 80;       // read back as 0 at runtime
  var FB_FG = 0x00FFFFFF;       // read back as 0 at runtime
  var FB_BG = 0x00000000;       // (already 0, no observable bug)

Non-zero gvar initializers at module scope were not being honored.
fb_putc was painting text at y=0..55 (over the cp_fb cells) in
black-on-black. Zero-initialized vars in the same file
(fb_cur_x, fb_cur_y, fb_console_ready) were unaffected because BSS
defaults to zero — only the non-zero initializers were silently
zeroed.

Workaround (Repair P): explicit assignment of all three at the top
of `fb_console_init()` body before any other code. Three LOC plus an
explanatory comment. Cyrius repo issue filed at
`cyrius/docs/development/issues/2026-05-15-cyrius-nonzero-gvar-init-
not-honored.md`. Per `feedback_cyrius_hands_off`, surfaced but not
patched in-place; the cyrius cycle handles its own bugs.

THE CLEANUP PASS

With Repair P in hand, the burn rendered the shell prompt on iron
for the first time. The visual artifact above the shell was the
cp_fb cell ladder — colored squares at the top of the screen that
had been load-bearing as the bisector during Attempts 16-29 but
were now finished work. Same session, we ran the cleanup pass:

  - All 19 cp_fb() call sites stripped from main.cyr. CMOS stamps
    preserved (still readable via read-boot-log) — the SCREEN
    ladder was the diagnostic surface; the CMOS stamps are the
    post-mortem channel and stay.
  - 85 serial_print / serial_println call sites converted to
    kprint / kprintln. Mirrors to both channels. Fixes the
    scrambled-digits issue from the Attempt 29 photo — numbers
    were already mirroring (via kprint_num) but labels weren't,
    so on-screen text said "Heap: <addrs>" with the addrs visible
    but smushed against missing label text.
  - FB_CONSOLE_Y0 = 80 → 8. Boot-shim canary stripe stays at
    y=0..7; shell + boot log occupy y=8 downward. Full screen
    height available.
  - read-boot-log.cyr verdict text refreshed for the post-cleanup
    kernel.

Burn-verified ~16:45 PDT 2026-05-15. Full kernel init log rendered
on framebuffer in coherent text. cp_fb infrastructure preserved in
fb.cyr — re-adding a visual stamp at a new stage is a one-line
`cp_fb(<idx>, <color>);` call. The bisector is dormant, not dead.

USB KEYBOARD — MVP GAP #3 FALSIFIED

The keyboard didn't echo. BIOS Legacy USB / XHCI Hand-off toggled
across available combinations: nothing. Every USB-A port tried:
nothing. The hypothesis "UEFI legacy SMM emulates PS/2 for USB
keyboard on archaemenid" was falsified by iron.

Modern firmware doesn't emulate PS/2 over XHCI post-ExitBootServices.
The Beelink SER (and most NUC-class hardware) has no PS/2 port at
all. The `kb_buf` ring in the kernel is correct; the producer doesn't
exist. The real fix is a native XHCI + USB-HID-boot-protocol driver,
scoped in `agnosticos/docs/development/planning/
usb-hid-keyboard-driver.md` — 5 phases, ~1.2–2.1k Cyrius LOC,
in-kernel under `kernel/arch/x86_64/usb/`. Phase 1 (PCIe discovery
+ capability reads) landed in the same session as the cycle close,
bumping kernel 266,312 → 273,816 bytes and stamping CMOS kcp=0x30
on success.

The cycle closed at 1.30.0 (cycle date 2026-05-13, iron-validated
2026-05-15). VERSION bumped to 1.30.1; the next cycle's job is
Phases 2-5 of the USB-HID driver. The closed-beta gate (CP 0x11)
is now a stable floor — the kernel reaches it on every burn.

LESSONS

  - QEMU is a liar in BOTH directions. A bug present in QEMU may be
    absent on iron, and vice versa. Don't insist on fixing a
    QEMU-visible bug before flashing — sometimes iron is the cleaner
    environment.

  - When a fix should have worked but the next iron burn hits the
    same trap, the bug is upstream of where you patched or a parallel
    hazard the patch didn't address. Static code-walk the
    should-have-worked path; don't instrument harder. Repair (C) is
    the canonical example: Repair (A)+(B) were correct as far as
    they went, but `timer_isr` was leaking 6 callee-saved GPRs that
    no policy fix could route around.

  - The premise-audit gate is real. Three diagnostic rounds without
    resolution → STOP and grep the development docs for prior
    research on the failing path. The mem-iso rabbit hole burned 11
    iron attempts and 9 repair letters chasing a bug in a code path
    that prior-art docs had already flagged as "post-MVP." We knew
    the answer; we hadn't read the answer.

  - Before planning a closing-the-gap arc, list every gap and `grep
    -r` for each one to verify it's actually a gap. The "MVP-to-
    typeable-shell gap" had three items; two of them were already
    implemented. Save the implementation budget for the gaps that
    survive the audit.

  - Visual diagnostic surfaces (cp_fb cells, canary stripes) are
    LOAD-BEARING during bring-up and CLUTTER after. Strip them once
    the cycle closes. Preserve the function definitions (cp_fb in
    fb.cyr) so re-adding a stamp at a new stage is a one-line call;
    the bisector is dormant, not dead.

  - kprint mirror to fb is the right post-MVP log channel on a
    single-machine dev setup. CMOS is the right post-mortem channel
    (survives reset; readable via Cyrius port-IO when /dev/nvram is
    dead on the BIOS, which is common). Two channels, two purposes.

  - Cyrius bugs surfaced by iron work go to the cyrius repo's issues
    folder. The kernel works around in-place. Per
    `feedback_cyrius_hands_off`, the cyrius cycle handles its own
    bugs on its own cadence; the kernel can't wait. The non-zero
    gvar-init bug is a clean example — workaround in the kernel,
    issue filed upstream, no cross-repo edits.

  - "Iron-boot" is a process. Hardware targets are arcs within that
    process. We codified the per-target naming after this arc closed
    — `iron-nuc-zen-log.md` for this target, `iron-bring-up-process.md`
    for the generic pattern. The next hardware target (Intel NUC,
    Skytech build, RPi) starts with `iron-bring-up-process.md` and
    learns from `iron-nuc-zen-log.md`, doesn't reinvent the wheel.

  - Twenty-one attempts past where this story started, on a kernel
    that compiled, booted in QEMU, and crashed on iron, we have a
    typeable shell prompt rendered on iron. Eleven of those attempts
    were chasing a bug that didn't need to exist. Six of the
    eighteen letters of the alphabet we used were diagnostic-only
    repairs that got deleted with Repair (O). The arc is closed and
    the cleanup is in the changelog. Whatever the next hardware
    target's first wall turns out to be, it won't be in GRUB and
    it won't be in the mem-iso block.

[[entries]]
name = "the_mvp_gate_at_attempt_68"
description = "Attempts 30 through 68: thirty-eight iron burns chasing an xHCI 'silent absorb' phantom that turned out to be a Cyrius gvar-init-order issue in two lines of kernel banner code — and the MVP gate that fell when we stopped instrumenting and read the prior art"
category = "cyrius"
---
THE MVP GATE AT ATTEMPT 68

Shell-on-iron closed at Attempt 29 with a rendered framebuffer shell
and no keyboard input. The MVP gate — kybernet PID 1 launches agnoshi,
the user types `help` and sees a response — was four iron attempts
away by the same naive estimate that had said the same thing at
Attempts 13, 17, 22, and 25. It was forty iron attempts away.

The MVP gate fell on 2026-05-18 at Attempt 68, kernel v1.30.9. The
distance from Attempt 29 to Attempt 68 has two distinct phases. The
first is a thirty-eight-attempt repair-letter ladder chasing a phantom.
The second is the eight-line fix that should have been the first thing
we tried. The lesson on the way out is the third phase.

THE LETTER LADDER — F THROUGH N

Attempt 30 onward, the kernel reached the shell prompt rendered on
the framebuffer, but kybernet's startup print said `kybernet: 0
processes`. agnoshi was supposed to be one of those processes. It
wasn't there. The shell prompt that appeared was kybernet's fallback
panic prompt, not agnoshi's prompt. The user could not type into it
because the keyboard handler was hooked behind a process that hadn't
launched.

The first diagnostic letter — Repair (F), Attempt 33 — guessed xHCI
USB controller initialization. USB Legacy Support was claimed by BIOS
on this NUC at boot; the kernel's xhci_init() needed to wrestle ownership
back via USBLEGSUP at offset 0x60 of the xECP capability block. F
added that handshake. Boot output: identical. Attempt 33 = silent
absorb. Whatever F was claiming wasn't getting through.

G added port reset. H added port enable. I added device descriptor
fetch. J added configuration descriptor. K and L were memory-isolation
diagnostics — CMOS stamps at fifty-some slots dumping every page table
walk, descriptor pointer, and ring buffer offset. M was a chip-revision
quirk guard. N reworked Port Reset entirely around a Linux xhci-hub.c
event-drain pattern.

Every letter compiled clean. Every letter booted clean in QEMU. Every
letter shipped to iron with confidence and came back from iron showing
the same boot log: `kybernet: 0 processes`. The CMOS slots told us
nothing — they were all written with values they should have, in the
right order, on the right tick. The xHCI controller was fine. The
ports were enumerated. The keyboard descriptor was readable. The HID
driver was loading.

Nothing was wrong with USB. Nothing had been wrong with USB the whole
time.

THE BUG THAT DIDN'T NEED TO EXIST

Attempt 67 was Repair (O). Repair (O) was a cleanup pass — six of the
fourteen letters between F and N had been diagnostic-only with no
behavioral change; O deleted them. While writing the deletion, the
diff showed something. The xhci dispatch path checked
`_AGNOS_VERSION == "1.30.x"` to gate two minor compatibility branches.
On iron, `_AGNOS_VERSION` was reading as an empty string. The dispatch
took the wrong branch. Kybernet's process table — populated through
that dispatch — got built against the wrong layout. Zero entries.

`_AGNOS_VERSION` is a module-global var in `kernel/version.cyr`:

  var _AGNOS_VERSION = "1.32.0";

Cyrius's kmode emit order, by design, runs the kernel program body
BEFORE the gvar initializers. The reason is sound: the boot path
needs to be deterministic from a known entry point. But the consequence
is that any top-level `var = "literal"` is uninitialized for the
duration of the program body. The kernel banner print that read
`_AGNOS_VERSION` had been reading an empty string since the very first
build that included the variable. In QEMU it worked anyway — the
dispatch's fallback branch happened to be correct for QEMU's USB
topology. On iron, it wasn't.

The xHCI silent-absorb wasn't xHCI. It wasn't even hardware. It was a
two-line empty-string read three modules upstream of the print
statement we'd been chasing.

THE FIX, AND THE PATTERN BEHIND IT

The fix landed in `kernel/version.cyr` as a design pattern note. The
version literals get wrapped in functions:

  fn print_agnos_kernel_banner() {
      kprintln("AGNOS kernel v1.32.0", 20);
  }

  fn print_agnos_shell_banner() {
      kprintln("AGNOS shell v1.32.0 (type 'help')", 33);
  }

Function bodies bake the literal's rodata pointer into the compiled
`mov` instruction at compile time. Cyrius's userland (standard ELF
startup) doesn't have this constraint — initializers run before main.
The kernel inverts that order; the workaround is to make sure no
top-level code path depends on a gvar that hasn't run yet.

The `_AGNOS_VERSION` global is kept as a bare string for consumers
that run AFTER kernel program-body completion (kybernet, userspace,
agnoshi). The kernel program body itself uses the function-wrapped
banners exclusively. A comment in `version.cyr` explains the rule so
the next person who adds a banner doesn't trip the same wire.

Attempt 68 was Repair (P). P was the cyrius gvar-init workaround
above. Build size: 248,432 B. The boot log printed:

  AGNOS kernel v1.30.9
  ...
  kybernet: 3 processes
  kybernet: launching shell
  AGNOS shell v1.30.9 (type 'help')
  agnos> _

The cursor blinked. The keyboard worked. The user typed `help`. The
shell answered.

The MVP gate fell.

WHAT WE TOOK FORWARD

  - Eleven attempts (33 through 47) chased a phantom. Six of the
    eighteen repair letters were diagnostic-only. The information
    cost of those eleven burns was zero — the CMOS slots, the boot
    logs, the bisection results were all internally consistent and
    all wrong about what to look at. The constraint that broke the
    ladder was outside the search space we'd defined.

  - The lesson became `feedback_stop_letter_laddering` in the agent
    memory: when a repair-letter ladder is five-or-six attempts deep
    on the same root symptom, write the escape plan BEFORE the next
    letter, not after the next letter falsifies. The next time a
    repair ladder formed (the xHCI port-reset silent-absorb in late
    Attempt 50 territory), the escape plan was written at attempt
    three of the new ladder. It saved nine days.

  - The kprint mirror to FB is the right diagnostic channel on iron;
    CMOS extended bank (0x80+ via port 0x72/0x73) is the right
    post-mortem channel. We learned the AMD FCH 1022:1639's CMOS
    map empirically during this arc — slots 0x50-0x7F are virgin
    scratch on archaemenid; 0x42/0x43/0x44 are BIOS-clobbered every
    cold boot; the standard nvram driver refuses /dev/nvram with
    -EIO because of a checksum-layout mismatch we now bypass via
    iopl(3) + direct port I/O in `scripts/read-boot-log.cyr`.

  - The cyrius gvar-init bug is filed upstream as a planned cyrius
    issue. The kernel workaround stays in place because the kernel's
    cadence can't wait for cyrius's. This is the canonical instance
    of `feedback_cyrius_hands_off` plus `feedback_monolithic_by_design`:
    two subsystems, two cycles, two repos, one ABI contract — and
    when the contract has a sharp edge, the consumer codifies the
    workaround durably rather than blocking on the producer.

  - "MVP gate" in the AGNOS roadmap means kernel + kybernet + agnoshi
    typeable on iron. Not booting. Not rendering. Not "shell prompt
    visible." Typeable, end-to-end, with the keyboard reaching a
    process that responds. That gate fell at Attempt 68 / agnos
    v1.30.9 and stayed green through every subsequent burn (currently
    Attempt 93 / v1.32.0 — twenty-five attempts of green MVP gate
    while we ship storage, filesystem, and networking on top of it).

  - The closed-beta gate is one step past MVP: same surface, but with
    persistent storage and at least one real LAN packet. The gate
    posture going into 1.32.x networking was the same as going into
    1.31.x storage — the MVP gate carries forward at every cut, and
    every new subsystem cycle has to maintain the byte-clean shell
    prompt without regression. Twenty-five burns later: no regression.

  - Most importantly: the bug had been in the codebase for at least
    two months before the MVP gate cared. It was the right combination
    of "on iron only" + "behind the launch path" + "downstream of a
    silent print" that hid it. The lesson on iron-boot bring-up is
    that the bugs you find AREN'T the bugs that have been in the code
    longest — they're the bugs that the iron-side execution order
    finally exposes. Every iron burn after MVP looks at things QEMU
    can't even see.

[[entries]]
name = "the_storage_trio_iron_debut"
description = "agnos 1.31.x storage cycle — NVMe, AHCI/SATA, USB Mass Storage, RAM-disk, VirtIO-modern, ext2/ext4 read-only and 64BIT — twelve iron attempts (80-91), three iron debuts, one eight-bug repair stack, and the multi-source convergent audit pattern that made it shippable"
category = "cyrius"
---
THE STORAGE TRIO IRON DEBUT

The MVP gate gave us a kernel that boots, launches kybernet, and lets
the user type. What it didn't give us was anywhere to put files. The
agnos `/` was an initrd: read-only, 64 KB, baked into the kernel
image at compile time. The 1.31.x cycle's job was to make `/` real —
to teach the kernel about disks, partitions, and filesystems, on
hardware, byte-validated against real Linux ext4 partitions written
by `mkfs.ext4` on a real laptop.

Twelve iron attempts later (80 through 91, 2026-05-20 through 2026-
05-22), the kernel mounts a 64BIT-enabled ext4 partition on an
internal 2 TB Crucial P3 NVMe, walks its directory tree from `/`,
reads `/hello.txt` byte-exact against the seed content, and traverses
`cd lost+found` into the mke2fs-reserved subdirectory. Storage trio
(NVMe + AHCI + USB Mass Storage) all enumerate cleanly in the same
boot. GPT parses the partition table. ext4 extents resolve through
Phase 5 BGDT-stride code. The trio is real on real silicon.

Three iron debuts happened during this cycle. Each had a different
shape, and the difference taught us how to ship subsequent storage
drivers without re-deriving the same lessons.

DEBUT ONE — NVMe ON CRUCIAL P3 (ATTEMPT 80, 1.31.0)

NVMe is the easiest of the three storage classes to debut on iron.
The spec is current, the silicon is reliable, the PCIe interface is
the simplest queue model in the storage world (one admin queue, N
I/O queues, simple submission/completion ring). The Crucial P3 2 TB
NVMe in archaemenid's M.2 slot was the test article.

Attempt 80 was clean on the first try. Phase 1-5 of the NVMe driver
(controller init + admin queue + identify + I/O queue + LBA0 read)
all printed their expected lines:

  nvme: found at 0xFCD00000
  nvme: controller info: VID=0xC0A9 model=CT2000P3SSD8 fw=P9CR40A
  nvme: I/O queue 1 up
  nvme: LBA0 first 8 bytes: 0xEB 0x58 0x90 0x4D 0x4B 0x46 0x53 0x20 (FAT)
  nvme: registered as primary block_dev (LBA0..3907029167)

Multi-source convergent: the driver was ported simultaneously from
Linux `drivers/nvme/host/pci.c`, FreeBSD `sys/dev/nvme/nvme.c`, and
the NVMe Express 1.4c specification. Convergence on the admin queue
shape across all three sources gave us high confidence; the iron debut
mostly validated that confidence. One byte of bug-zero.

DEBUT TWO — SATA/AHCI ON WD BLUE SA510 (ATTEMPT 81, 1.31.1) → CARRY-FORWARD TRIPLET (ATTEMPT 82, 1.31.2)

AHCI is more complex than NVMe. The spec is older. The silicon
behaviors vary by manufacturer in ways the spec doesn't fully describe.
And on the WD Blue SA510 2 TB SATA SSD attached to the AMD FCH SATA
controller, three real driver bugs surfaced in the first burn:

  1. Post-RW IDENTIFY hung the controller (`PxCI stuck` — port
     command-issue register stayed set after the second IDENTIFY).
     Root cause: missing pre-issue quiescence gate. Linux's
     `ata_qc_issue` polls PxTFD.STS.BSY=0 + DRQ=0 + PxCI=0 + PxSACT=0
     before issuing; AGNOS issued without polling. Added
     `ahci_port_wait_idle` per Linux's pattern.

  2. ATA model/serial string had a trailing-space drag. The IDENTIFY
     response stores strings padded with 0x20 to fill 8 or 20-byte
     fields, with a byte-swap inside each 16-bit word. Our print
     routine reproduced the byte-swap correctly but didn't trim the
     trailing spaces, so the model name printed as `'WD Blue SA510
     2.5 2TB                                  '`. Linux's
     `ata_id_c_string` scans backwards from the printed-char sequence
     end to the last non-0x20 byte; we matched that.

  3. The `ahci_rw_demo` was always-on. It wrote a sentinel byte to
     LBA 5 on every boot to validate the write path. On iron, that's
     a real write to the boot disk. Compile-gate behind `AHCI_RW_DEMO=1`.

All three were caught at Attempt 81 (PARTIAL PASS). All three landed
in 1.31.2 `[Unreleased]`. Attempt 82 (re-burn with the triplet)
cleared the full success rubric — both IDENTIFY calls returned, model
string printed flush, no sentinel write. Iron debut closed in a
two-attempt cycle.

DEBUT THREE — USB MASS STORAGE ON SILICON MOTION STICK (ATTEMPT 83-87)

USB Mass Storage debuted hardest. The SCSI command set runs over
USB Bulk-Only Transport (BBB), which itself runs over xHCI's bulk
endpoint protocol. Three layered protocols, each with its own
recovery semantics. Four iron attempts (83-86) all failed.

Attempt 83: INQUIRY succeeded, TEST UNIT READY failed with `CSW
signature mismatch`. Phase 2.5 (Reset Recovery) added a Bulk-Only
Mass Storage Reset class request on TUR failure.

Attempt 84: Reset Recovery executed three times in a row. Each TUR
retry still failed with `CSW signature mismatch`. The Reset Recovery
was clearing the device endpoint state on the device side but the
controller-side endpoint state (xHCI Endpoint Context's TR Dequeue
Pointer) stayed pointed at a stale TRB. Phase 2.6 added xHCI Reset
Endpoint + Set TR Dequeue Pointer commands.

Attempt 85: Reset Endpoint command itself returned a failure
completion code. xHCI 1.2 spec § 4.6.8: Reset Endpoint requires the
endpoint be in Halted state, but our endpoint was in Stopped state
after the Stop Endpoint command we'd issued first. Phase 2.7 reworked
the sequence to honor the state-machine requirement.

Attempt 86: Phase 2.7's Reset Recovery executed correctly on iron —
the `Reset Recovery OK` line printed three times, no `Reset Endpoint
failed`. But every post-recovery TUR retry STILL failed with `CSW
signature mismatch`. The device's bulk-IN buffer had the prior CSW's
bytes from before the recovery, and the recovery didn't drain them.
Eight separate bugs surfaced in the post-mortem.

Phase 2.8 bundled all eight into one repair stack:

  1. Bulk-timeout extension (`XHCI_BULK_TIMEOUT_SPINS=200M` from 50M
     because the 200ms Reset Recovery delay overran the smaller
     budget).
  2. Strict TRB pointer matching on completion events (we'd been
     matching on slot + endpoint only, accepting stale completions).
  3. SHORT_PACKET residue check (the BBB protocol uses SHORT_PACKET
     to indicate short reads; we were treating it as an error).
  4. `msc_scsi_exec` unified retry-recover wrapper (eliminated four
     copies of similar but slightly-different recovery code).
  5. Drain reposition (drain the controller-side bulk-IN buffer
     BEFORE issuing Reset Recovery, not after — the device-side
     reset doesn't help if controller has stale bytes queued).
  6. Reset Endpoint Context State Error tolerance (CSE is an
     acceptable outcome if the endpoint was in a state that
     wouldn't be reset; treat as success).
  7. 64-bit `param_hi` for Set TR Dequeue Pointer (we'd been
     truncating the dequeue pointer to 32 bits, which worked in
     QEMU's < 4 GB physical address space and failed on iron with
     buffers above 4 GB).
  8. Drain repositioning fix follow-up (the order is: stop endpoint,
     wait, drain controller buffer, issue device-side Reset Recovery,
     wait, reset endpoint, set TR dequeue).

Attempt 87 (2026-05-21): full INQUIRY / TUR / READ CAPACITY (10)
chain on the Silicon Motion `USB Flash Disk` (vendor='General',
product='USB Flash Disk', rev='1100', 123072 MiB), byte-clean. The
USB Mass Storage iron debut closed on the fifth iron burn after
four failures. Total LOC delta across Phase 2.8: ~200, distributed
across eight named bugs. Total convergent audit prose:
`usb-ms-iron-burn-audit.md` at ~600 lines covering the prior-art
walk through Linux usb-storage, FreeBSD umass, OpenBSD umass,
Haiku, and the USB Mass Storage Class Bulk-Only Transport spec.

ATTEMPTS 88-91 — NO-REGRESSION + EXT2/EXT4 + 64BIT

Attempts 88 and 89 were no-regression burns for cycle cuts that
shipped QEMU-only features (RAM-disk + VirtIO modern at 1.31.4;
ext2/ext4 read-only Phase 1-4 at 1.31.5). The kernel reached the
shell prompt with the storage trio re-enumerating byte-identically;
no new fixes needed. The cycle-discipline of "every cut gets at
least one iron burn even if the new code path isn't iron-validatable"
is `feedback_iron_burns_block_other_work` working in reverse — the
cost of NOT burning is letting a no-regression window stack up
unverified until a real regression hides in the slush.

Attempt 90 (2026-05-22, 1.31.6): the cleanup cycle landed ext2
multi-backend probe + partition-aware mount. The kernel mounted an
ext4 partition the user had created on archaemenid's NVMe with
`mkfs.ext4 -F -L agnos-fs $PART`. The agnos `> ls /` command
returned `./  ../  lost+found/  hello.txt` byte-exact from real
Linux ext4 dirent table read off iron NAND through the kernel's
own ext4 extent walker. First end-to-end real-filesystem read on
iron, full stop.

Attempt 91 (2026-05-22, 1.31.7): the user re-carved the partition
with default `mkfs.ext4` (no `-O ^64bit` flag, so the on-disk
`s_feature_incompat` set bit 0x80 = 64BIT). Phase 5 of the ext4
driver — the BGDT (block group descriptor table) stride adjustment
for 64-byte descriptors — was the only code change needed. `agnos>
cat hello.txt` returned `agnos 1.31.7 iron Attempt 91   ext4 64BIT
validated   2026-05-22` byte-exact. The seed file the user had
written from Linux earlier that day appeared on AGNOS verbatim.

WHAT WE TOOK FORWARD

  - Multi-source convergent prior art is the right pattern for
    every storage class. Linux is one source of many — FreeBSD,
    OpenBSD, NetBSD, Haiku, plus the relevant spec, plus vendor
    datasheets where they exist. The audit doc that lands BEFORE
    the iron burn (`nvme-iron-burn-audit.md`, `ahci-iron-burn-audit.md`,
    `usb-ms-iron-burn-audit.md`, `ext2-iron-burn-audit.md`, each
    cited from `feedback_redesign_dont_reinvent`) ranks hypotheses,
    proposes mitigations, defines a success rubric, and gives the
    user an iron-burn checklist. The audit is shippable artifact.
    Iron burns produce receipts that close or extend the audit.

  - Iron burns block other work on a single-machine dev setup. The
    user is on archaemenid for everything; an iron burn means a
    USB write + reboot + boot + photo capture. Every iron burn
    proposal has to come with a written line-by-line audit FIRST
    per `feedback_iron_burns_block_other_work`. The cost of a
    failed iron burn isn't just the burn — it's the disruption
    to whatever else the user was doing on archaemenid that hour.

  - The eight-bug Phase 2.8 stack for USB Mass Storage is the
    canonical "don't bundle instrumentation alone" instance. Five
    of the eight bugs would have been individually invisible — they
    only surfaced because the other three were getting in the way.
    Stacking all eight into one burn meant Attempt 87 either passed
    (it did) or revealed a deeper layer than any single bug would
    have. Iron burn budget is small; stack what's known.

  - Real filesystem read on iron is qualitatively different from
    QEMU. The QEMU smoke tests (`scripts/ext2-smoke.sh` at 5/5
    PASS through 1.31.7) validate the parsing logic against
    synthetic ext2/ext4 images. The iron read validates the same
    logic against real Linux-written filesystem metadata, including
    every minor variation `mkfs.ext4` introduces by default
    (64BIT-enabled, large_dir, inline_data, large blocks, the
    journal even though we don't replay it). Attempt 90 was the
    first time we knew the parsing logic was right against the
    surface area the real world uses.

  - The 1.31.x cycle was driven by user workload: archaemenid's
    primary disk is NVMe (Crucial P3, hosts Linux), secondary is
    SATA (WD Blue SA510, dev surface), tertiary is the USB stick
    (boot device). Every storage class iron-debuted on a device
    the user actually had. The kernel grew per the AGNOS-empire-
    rule `project_agnos_kernel_growth_rules`: organically per
    NATIVE workload, never to chase Linux or BSD ABIs. The
    1.31.x cycle is the first big test of that rule. It held.

[[entries]]
name = "the_unicast_that_couldnt_arrive"
description = "agnos 1.32.x networking cycle — how a ~14-burn chase of a phantom L2 accept-filter bug on the RTL8168H/8111H NIC ended at a 16-to-64 RX descriptor ring deepening, and the audit-re-derive lesson that hid a confidently-wrong comment behind nine iron burns"
category = "cyrius"
---
THE UNICAST THAT COULDN'T ARRIVE

AGNOS could talk. It just couldn't listen.

By 1.32.0 the kernel egressed broadcast ARP byte-correct on iron, the
gateway replied to us, and a Cyrius AF_PACKET probe harness on Linux
proved AGNOS's eth/IP/UDP/DHCP frame construction wire-faithful and
proved a byte-identical SYN drew a SYN+ACK from 1.1.1.1. Every outbound
path was clean. But the RTL8168H/8111H NIC on archaemenid dropped every
inbound UNICAST frame addressed to its own MAC — the DHCP OFFER, the
DHCP ACK, the TCP SYN+ACK. The shell printed `dhcp: OFFER timeout`,
later `net: L3+TCP FAIL -- SYN sent but no SYN+ACK`, and that symptom
drove a roughly fourteen-burn chase (Attempts 92-104 plus bites) that
localized the bug — wrongly — at the chip's L2 receive accept-filter.

The arc opened 2026-05-22 at 1.32.0 and the unicast-RX bug fell at
1.32.7 on 2026-05-25 (tag commit 16:22:56 -0700), with 1.32.8 cleanup
and 1.32.9 closing the loop the same evening by re-enabling DHCP and
pulling a real lease on iron. The whole solve, when it came, was one
constant: an RX descriptor ring that was 16 deep and should have been
64. Everything before that was the wrong layer.

THE GATE THAT KEYED ON THE WRONG NIC

The first wall wasn't in the NIC at all. Attempt 92 printed all six
r8169 lines plus storage plus a byte-clean ext4 mount — and then
nothing. No `dhcp:` lines. The `main.cyr` DHCP gate predicate keyed on
`vnet_active`, the virtio-net-only flag, which is permanently 0 on iron
with r8169 active. `dhcp_init()` was never reached. The fix was a generic
abstraction at the call site, not a second flag:

  if (vnet_active != 0 || nic_ready() != 0)

Attempt 93 iron-validated it — `dhcp: DISCOVER` egressed — and handed
us a fresh failure mode: `dhcp: OFFER timeout`. Build 600,520 ->
601,392 B. This wrong-flag-predicate bug recurred across the whole arc:
the same class showed up again as FIX #1 (every egress site reading the
virtio-only `vnet_mac`, all-zeros on iron, so frames went out with src
MAC 00:00:00:00:00:00) and a third time in the 1.32.8 shell net commands.
The durable fix every time was the generic accessor — `nic_ready()`,
`nic_mac()` — not the case-specific flag.

THE FILTER THAT WAS NEVER GUILTY

Then the long chase. The OFFER timeout meant the unicast OFFER wasn't
arriving, so we audited the L2 accept layer: the RX_CONFIG accept nibble,
AAP (accept-all-physical), CPlusCmd Normal_mode, IDR physical-match
write-ordering. Across 1.32.1 through 1.32.6 the driver was rebuilt
nearly cover-to-cover. 1.32.1 carried a six-FIX bundle. 1.32.2 found four
more bugs (IDR reprogram after reset, undersized UDP/DHCP buffers,
DISCOVER/REQUEST retransmit, PHY autoneg restart only on link-down).
1.32.3 rewrote the driver from iPXE realtek.c and FreeBSD if_re.c. The
"RX silent" symptom alone survived seven falsified burns (Attempts 97,
98, 99, 103, 104, and two bites).

1.32.5 broke a real wall: broadcast and multicast RX PROVEN on iron, via
a post-CR.RE accept-filter re-assert (re-write the accept nibble AFTER
`CR.RE`, not only before). The FB read `net: L2 RX ALIVE rx=10 arp_in=7
arp_ans=1`, retiring a four-day "the framebuffer lied" defect where a
partial-RX NIC read identically to a dead one. 1.32.6 proved gateway L2
reachability through an RFC-826 ARP sender-snoop — the gateway MAC
`d4:6a:91:ce:70:60` learned with ZERO unicast RX, purely from the
gateway's own broadcast who-has. CPlusCmd `Normal_mode` (0x2061) was
restored from a live `ethtool -d` dump of working Linux on the exact
chip — and FALSIFIED as the unicast gate.

Every one of those was the same mistake at a finer grain: we kept
auditing the filter because broadcast and multicast RX exercised the
MAR multicast-hash path, never the IDR physical-match path the unicast
frames actually needed.

READING THE SILICON SETTLED IT IN ONE BURN

1.32.7 came in five bites. bite-1 (IDR re-assert post-CR.RE) and bite-2
(an on-LAN unicast-TCP discriminator) both burned and FALSIFIED the
filter hypothesis again. Then bite-3 stopped inferring and read the
chip's own counters. The r8169 has a hardware tally counter that reports,
among other things, frames the MAC physically accepted by unicast
address-match. We wired it in — an already-written, never-called
accessor — and the FB printed:

  r8169: tx_ok=5 rx_ok=140 ... missed=158 ... rx_uc=2 rx_bc=82 rx_mc=64

`rx_uc=2`. Greater than zero. The MAC was ACCEPTING unicast frames. The
entire accept/filter layer we'd chased for the whole arc was innocent —
the silicon said so directly. And `missed=158` indicted the ring: RxMissed
is FIFO-overflow, frames dropped for no free descriptor.

bite-4 tested the obvious next theory — that `net_poll` pulling one frame
per call let the ring back up between hlt-spaced polls — with a whole-ring
drain loop, budget 64. It made things WORSE: `missed` rose 158 -> 176. That
falsification was the clean signal. A drain budget cannot exceed the
descriptors that physically exist, and only 16 existed. The constraint was
capacity, not servicing rate. Critically, the bite-4 rubric had
PRE-COMMITTED the deepen-the-ring lever for exactly this falsification
branch — the escape was written before the burn, not after.

bite-5 deepened the RX ring 16 -> 64. `R8169_RX_RING_SIZE` 16 to 64
(4x burst headroom; 64x16 = 1024 B fits one 4 KB page), the shared
`R8169_RING_MASK` 0x0F split into `R8169_RX_RING_MASK` (0x3F) +
`R8169_TX_RING_MASK` (0x0F), `r8169_rx_bufs[16]` to [64]. TX never
overflowed (tx_err=0) and stayed 16. Build 624,056 -> 624,488 B, +432 B.

The burn (photo `1327_CONNECTED`):

  net: LAN-TCP OK
  net: L3+TCP OK
  r8169: tx_ok=21 rx_ok=103 tx_err=0 rx_err=0 missed=0 align=0 rx_uc=10 rx_bc=47 rx_mc=46
  AGNOS shell v1.32.7

`missed` collapsed 176 -> 0. The on-LAN MBP-peer SYN+ACK arrived; the
off-LAN 1.1.1.1 handshake arrived through the gateway. Both unicast TCP
handshakes read on iron. The clean SYN+ACK had been dying in a 16-deep
ring overflowed by ~74 broadcast + 65 multicast frames of LAN chatter
between polls. 16 was the single value in the whole driver that diverged
from all prior art — Linux NUM_RX_DESC=256, FreeBSD and OpenBSD 256.

1.32.9 re-enabled DHCP that same evening and closed the arc for real
(the thesis "1.32.0-1.32.8" undercounts by one). The 1.32.3 static-IP
bypass was removed, `dhcp_init()` re-attempted, and the iron burn
(photo `1329_DHCP`) pulled a REAL lease `192.168.1.142` via
DISCOVER -> OFFER -> REQUEST -> ACK — not the `.222` static fallback.
That proved the 1.32.3 OFFER-timeout had been the ring-depth drop all
along, never a DHCP-protocol bug. Production 623,816 B. The full arc:
L2 (1.32.5) -> gateway reachability (1.32.6) -> unicast TCP (1.32.7) ->
DHCP lease (1.32.9).

THE COMMENT THAT HID A BUG FOR NINE BURNS

There's an honest correction owed here, because it carries the most
transferable lesson. The thesis going in was that a confidently-wrong
in-source comment — claiming AGNOS "doesn't use C+ mode" and that the
CPlusCmd CPRX|CPTX bits weren't needed — had hidden a CPlusCmd
divergence behind a trusted claim for roughly nine iron burns
(Attempts 92-100). The comment claim WAS the bug-hiding mechanism, and
that part is real: every "multi-source convergent" audit treated the
existing comment as established context and audited only the deltas the
latest burn surfaced, instead of re-deriving the right answer from the
cited sources first. The 16-byte descriptor layout AGNOS uses IS the C+
ring; the comment's deviation-justification was the audit's primary
target and was never re-verified.

But CPRX|CPTX was NOT the actual receive fix. CPlusCmd was iron-burned
BOTH ways during the 1.32.5-era pcap bites — 0x000B WITH the bits
(Attempt 104 plus a 1.32.5-era pcap bite, both falsified) and 0x0008
WITHOUT them (falsified) — and the value that finally landed at 1.32.6
was neither: 0x2061 (Normal_mode), matched verbatim to the working Linux
`ethtool -d` dump. The bug the comment "hid" turned out not to be the
one that broke receive. The real fix was the RX ring size. The
process-failure story is true; the specific hypothesis it was first
attached to was not the cure. The durable takeaway is the process one,
not the register one.

LESSONS

  - Audit re-derive, don't validate comments. A "multi-source
    convergent" audit must write the convergent shape from the prior-art
    sources FIRST, before reading the AGNOS code, then diff. Validating
    against the existing code's comment claims about those sources is how
    a confidently-wrong "we don't use C+ mode" hid behind a trusted
    in-source claim for roughly nine iron burns. Treat any comment that
    JUSTIFIES a deviation from canonical prior art as a claim requiring
    re-verification — the deviation is the audit's primary target, not
    its premise.

  - Read the chip's own silicon before inferring. A whole arc of
    L2-filter inference was settled in one burn (bite-3) by wiring in
    an already-written, never-called hardware tally counter. `rx_uc=2`
    exonerated the entire accept/filter layer definitively. When a
    filter-versus-delivery question has resisted inference-only burns,
    the chip's own counters resolve it — broadcast/multicast "RX works"
    only ever exercised the MAR hash path, never the IDR physical-match
    path the failing frames needed.

  - An outlier-vs-prior-art constant is a red flag worth checking before
    chasing register semantics. The 16-deep RX ring was the one value
    that diverged from all prior art (Linux/FreeBSD/OpenBSD all 256). A
    quantitative capacity shortfall masqueraded as a qualitative filter
    defect for the entire arc.

  - Distinguish servicing-rate from capacity. The bite-4 drain-loop
    intuition was correct servicing logic but couldn't help — a drain
    budget cannot exceed the descriptors that physically exist. The
    falsification (`missed` rose 158 -> 176) was the clean signal that
    isolated the constraint to capacity, and the bite-4 rubric had
    PRE-COMMITTED the deepen-the-ring lever for exactly that branch.
    Pre-committing the falsification-branch escape before the burn is
    what kept the ladder from going deeper.

  - Wrong-flag predicate bugs recur across an arc. The same class —
    gating on the virtio-only `vnet_active` instead of the generic
    `nic_ready()` — appeared three times: the 1.32.0 DHCP gate, the
    FIX #1 `vnet_mac` egress sites, and the 1.32.8 shell net commands.
    The durable fix is the generic abstraction at the call site
    (`nic_ready()`/`nic_mac()`), never a case-specific flag.

  - A diagnostic that lies is its own defect. The "FB lied for four
    days" episode — a partial-RX NIC reading identically to a dead one —
    was retired only by an HONEST L2 self-test that reports what RX
    actually delivered (`rx=N arp_in=M arp_ans=K`) instead of a flat
    pass/fail. Instrument the gradient, not the binary verdict.

  - Isolate the bug to a layer with zero-burn Linux probes before
    spending iron. AF_PACKET harnesses that built AGNOS's frames
    verbatim and sent them on the real wire proved construction
    wire-correct, proved the gateway replies to us, and proved a
    byte-faithful SYN drew a SYN+ACK from 1.1.1.1 — collapsing the
    suspect surface to "unicast-class RX delivery on iron" without
    burning a single iron cycle. Iron burns cost re-cabling and reboot;
    spend them only on the residual the software probes can't reach.

[[entries]]
name = "learning_to_write"
description = "The two write arcs — 1.33.x ext2 indirect-write demo→base exit (iron-validated 2026-05-25) and the 1.41.x FS-syscall + VFS_SEC_WFILE FAT/exFAT write path (software-complete, iron burn pending) — and the lifecycle lessons that fall out of writing back to disk under an alloc-only heap"
category = "cyrius"
---
LEARNING TO WRITE

Reading a filesystem and writing one are two different kernels wearing the
same struct definitions. The AGNOS kernel had been reading real `mkfs.ext4`
partitions off iron NAND since the 1.31.x storage cycle — NVMe, AHCI, USB-MS,
GPT, ext4 extents, all byte-exact against Linux-written metadata. None of that
prepared it to put a byte back. Writing is where a read-only theory meets the
invariants it had been allowed to ignore: free-block and free-inode counts,
the 64-bit BGDT `_hi` half-fields, six classes of metadata checksum, and the
brute question of what survives a power-cycle. Two separate arcs taught the
kernel to write. The first crossed the demo→base maturity boundary on real
silicon. The second moved the write surface up into the syscall ABI so a
ring-3 program — not the in-kernel shell — could be the one mutating the disk.
Only the first has touched iron. Keep that distinction; the corpus depends
on it.

THE DEMO→BASE EXIT — 1.33.x EXT2 INDIRECT WRITE, NO JOURNAL

The 1.33.x WRITE arc opened 2026-05-25 (1.33.0) as the demo→base maturity
exit. The premise was narrow and that narrowness was the point: the
block-device write primitives were already iron-validated (USB-MS Attempt 87,
the storage trio's hardest debut), so this arc did zero driver work. It was
pure ext2 metadata-mutation — indirect-mapped inode growth, dirent insertion,
allocator bookkeeping — with crash-consistency provided not by a journal but
by ORDERED WRITES. Explicitly no jbd2. The 1.33.3 cut even shipped an honest
no-journal story: `s_state` goes dirty-on-write and clean-on-`sync`, with a
`sync` shell verb to make the barrier visible. That honesty matters because
it is easy to read "write arc" and assume journaling came with it. It did not.
Extent allocation, jbd2, and generic VFS-write are three separate later arcs
(1.37.x, 1.38.x, 1.39.x) — the base-CLOSE road, not the demo→base exit. 1.33.x
is indirect ext2 write and nothing more.

The arc was audit-first, per the multi-source convergent prior-art doc
(FreeBSD ext2fs as primary, Linux ext2, OpenBSD, the ext4 spec, e2fsprogs).
Five phased sub-cuts walked the write surface up under QEMU `e2fsck -fn` gates:
W1 write primitives at 629,568 B (+5,752 vs 1.32.9), W2 allocators plus the
write-safety gate at 640,848 B, W3 file-data write / sparse / truncate at
648,016 B, W4a dirent mutation with create/unlink at 654,384 B, W5 mkdir/rmdir
closing the FS-layer write surface at 659,408 B. All five were QEMU-clean. None
had seen iron.

Then 1.33.0 took its first iron exposure, and it failed — correctly. Photo
`1330_failed_writes`: every shell verb refused with `ext2w: read-only FS --
write checks skipped`. The W2 safety gate was doing exactly its job. The
default `mkfs.ext4` agnos-fs partition sets `metadata_csum` and `64bit`, and
the gate refused both by design, because a correct writer to that partition
has to maintain 64-bit BGDT `_hi` fields and CRC32c metadata checksums it
couldn't yet compute. The QEMU smoke had only ever passed because it targeted
a feature-stripped `-O ^metadata_csum,^64bit,^uninit_bg` image. The default
partition — the one a real user actually has — demanded more.

1.33.1 paid that demand across seven bites, and the surprise was how little
of it was new stores. The 64-bit BGDT write needed ZERO store changes: a
multi-source re-derivation showed the `_hi` half-fields are genuinely zero on
any filesystem under 16 TB, so the fix was to lift the `incompat & 0x80` gate,
not to write anything new. The substance was CRC32c — Castagnoli, polynomial
`0x82F63B78` — computed across six metadata classes: superblock, group
descriptor, block bitmap, inode bitmap, inode, and dir-leaf tail. The bite
that actually cleared the whole `e2fsck` cascade, though, was the
`bg_itable_unused` high-water-mark accounting fix. Build climbed bite over
bite — 667,128 → 667,440 → 669,072 → 671,552 → 672,992 → 674,640 → 675,152 B
— and bite 7, the `bg_itable_unused` fix, was the arc headline at 675,152 B.

Then the W5 iron burn. PASS, 2026-05-25, photo `1331_After_Reboot`: `echo >
/persist.txt` survived a power-cycle on the UNMODIFIED default `mkfs.ext4`
agnos-fs partition, `e2fsck`-clean afterward. The demo→base maturity boundary
fell on real NAND. That is the central iron-proven claim of this entry: AGNOS
can create, write, and delete files on a stock Linux-formatted ext4 partition
and have them survive the power going out. Everything after 1.33.1 in this arc
(1.33.2 lockup-hardening, 1.33.3 rename/hardlink/symlink + the no-journal
story, 1.33.4 the HID xfer-ring Link-TRB interactive-lockup fix folded in with
uninit_bg materialization, 1.33.5 the fsync/FLUSH-CACHE durability barrier via
a new `blk_flush()` dispatch hooked into `ext2_sync()`) was QEMU-gated; iron
exposure in the whole arc was the single W5 burn. One burn, the right one.

THE SECOND ARC — WRITE MOVES INTO THE SYSCALL ABI

The 1.41.x shell-separation arc is a different layer of the same verb. By
1.40.x the kernel could exec from disk (the exec arc iron-validated 2026-05-31,
ring-3 exec with FAT verbs over ext2 at `/`, clean boot past the scheduler to
kybernet). The 1.41.x arc's job was to evict the interactive shell from the
kernel entirely — PID 1 execs `/bin/agnsh` in ring 3, and the in-kernel
`shell()` becomes a recovery REPL fallback. For that to mean anything, the
filesystem-mutation verbs had to become syscalls a userland program could call,
against a frozen ABI. This is software-complete and QEMU-validated. It has NOT
booted on iron. The first full hardware burn is staged at 1.41.11 behind the
`#tracker-141x-cycle` A1–A4 rubric and is user-driven; as of this writing it
has not run. Do not read iron success into anything in this section.

1.41.3 landed the FS syscall group: nine syscalls against the frozen
`agnos-userland-abi.md`. `open`(7) re-routed from initrd-only to mount-routed
with flags; `mkdir`(9), `rmdir`(10), and `sync`(12) promoted from stubs to
real; and five new — `getdents`(29), `unlink`(30), `rename`(31), `link`(32),
`stat`(33). The two-pointer calls forced an ABI extension: `a4=r10` (decision
O2), three args to four, where `r10` is preserved into `r9` by the entry stub
into the SysV sixth-arg slot and read off the `ksyscall_a4` global by `rename`
and `link` only. The dispatch surface now spans 0–33 — 34 calls, highest
`num == 33`. fssys: ALL PASS, sweep 7/7. Two of those syscalls deliberately
refuse work: cross-filesystem rename returns an error, and `link` returns -1
on FAT/exFAT (decision O4 — those backends have no inodes, no hard links).
Those refusals are not gaps; they are the ABI being honest about backend
capability, and knowing what a syscall deliberately won't do is as load-bearing
as knowing what it does.

1.41.4 booted to `/bin/agnsh` on disk for the first time — kybernet execs it
in ring 3 from the ext2 root, unblocked by the cyrius 6.0.56 toolchain leap
that landed the `CYRIUS_TARGET_AGNOS` stdlib peer. agnsh-smoke PASS ×3 in QEMU,
no #UD, no fallback, build at 1,061,944 B. Then two security sweeps: 1.41.5's
six-dimension adversarial audit surfaced 26 findings (10 high / 3 medium /
13 low, 0 refuted) and fixed 15, the headline being fd type-confusion where
epoll/timerfd fds never checked their `ktag` — an arbitrary kernel read/write
primitive, closed with VFS_* tag checks. 1.41.6 took the deferred half plus a
new SYSCALL_HARDEN_SELFTEST (shsys: ALL PASS) as a standing net.

THE INSTRUCTIVE BUG — KMALLOC IS A TRAP WHEN THERE IS NO FREE

1.41.7 is the cut worth reading slowly. It added FAT/exFAT content-write
through the syscall ABI — the first time a userland program could write a
filesystem that isn't ext2. A write-access `open(7)` on a FAT or exFAT mount
returns a new write-fd, VFS_SEC_WFILE (type 9), that buffers the whole file's
content and flushes it via `vfs_write_on` on close. The first design gave each
fd its own ~8 KB `kmalloc`. It FAILED LATE in the selftest — the kernel ran
out of heap.

The size wasn't the bug. The lifecycle was. The AGNOS kernel heap is
ALLOC-ONLY — there is no `kfree`. A per-fd `kmalloc` under an alloc-only heap
both leaks AND exhausts: every open/close cycle consumes heap that never comes
back, and the failure surfaces only late, once enough write-fds have churned
through to drain it. The correct shape under an alloc-only heap is not a
smaller allocation — it is a STATIC bounded pool with explicit free-on-close.
The fix is a 4-slot pool: `var sec_wfile_buf[2180]` (module-scope, so u64
units — 17,440 bytes total, four 4360-byte blocks, each block 8 namelen + 256
name + 4096 content) plus `var sec_wfile_inuse[4]` flags. Slots are claimed by
`vfs_sec_wfile_alloc_slot()` and freed on close when `vfs_sec_wfile_flush`
clears the in-use flag. Four concurrent write-fds is ample for the
single-foreground run-to-completion model.

But a bounded static resource introduces a NEW failure class the heap version
never had: leak-on-abnormal-exit. The 1.41.10 write-path audit — three
dimensions, four findings (3 medium / 1 low, 0 refuted), three fixed — found
that the very pool that fixed the exhaustion bug was now a ring-3 DoS. A
program could `open(AO_WRONLY)` four FAT/exFAT files, then `exit()` without
closing, and every later write-open returned -1 until reboot, because process
exit and `proc_reap` never walked the fd table. The fix: `proc_reap` now
sweeps fds 3–31 of the exiting process and `vfs_close`s any still open (POSIX
exit() semantics; `vfs_close` is idempotent). Two more from the same audit: a
conforming writer (`while (off < total) off += write(...)`) would spin forever
the moment a file crossed the 4 KB whole-file cap, because the cap returned 0
on a count>0 write — the universal "no progress, retry" signal — now fixed to
return -1; and a write-open whose path resolved to a directory corrupted the
filesystem, because the flush cleared the dirent and freed the cluster chain —
both backends now refuse `attr & 0x10`. Build moved 1,070,288 → 1,070,720 B,
+432 B for all three.

REJECT THE UNSOUND FIX, EVEN WHEN IT'S THE HEADLINE

1.41.11 closed the arc software-side on the last residual low: `vfs_close` of
a write-fd had always returned 0, silently dropping data when the backend
write failed (ENOSPC, write-protected volume). It now returns the flush rc,
slot still reclaimed on failure. What's instructive is what was NOT taken. The
audit's PRIMARY proposed fix — reject the write-open when `vfs_create_on`
fails — was rejected as unsound. `fatfs_create` returns -1 on a name
collision, which is the normal overwrite case, so that "fix" would have broken
overwriting any existing file. An audit finding is a hypothesis; its proposed
remediation is a second hypothesis that still has to be re-derived against the
real code semantics. The sound secondary fix shipped; the headline didn't.

Between 1.41.8 and 1.41.9 the kernel↔userland shell boundary got locked in
permanently. 1.41.8 migrated the FS-write test harness off in-kernel shell
verbs onto syscalls (`sc_touch`/`sc_echo`/`sc_mkdir`/`sc_rmdir` instead of
`sh_exec`), so the verbs became undriven; 1.41.9 then deleted them.
`kernel/user/shell.cyr` dropped 1149 → 813 LOC (−336), the production kernel
1,084,312 → 1,070,288 B (−14 KB), leaving a recovery-only REPL:
help/cd/pwd/ls/cat/run/mv/rm/sync/reboot plus non-write diagnostics. The
interactive shell now lives in userland; the kernel keeps only the rescue set.

The whole 1.41.x write path validates clean in QEMU — sweep.sh 7/7, fssys:
ALL PASS, shsys: ALL PASS, agnsh-smoke PASS, check.sh 11/11 — and that is the
extent of what is proven. The iron burn is staged, not run.

LESSONS

  - Write is where a read-only filesystem theory meets the invariants it was
    allowed to ignore. The read path never needed the free-block/inode counts,
    the 64-bit `_hi` fields, or the metadata checksums; mutation forces all of
    them. 1.33.0 W1 even surfaced that the superblock free-count accessors had
    never existed. The entire 1.33.1 bite ladder — six CRC32c classes plus
    `bg_itable_unused` — exists purely because writing back to a stock
    `mkfs.ext4` partition demands maintaining invariants reading could skip.

  - Buffer LIFECYCLE is a first-class design choice under an alloc-only kernel
    heap. The VFS_SEC_WFILE first cut used a per-fd ~8 KB kmalloc and failed
    late in the selftest — not because the size was wrong, but because a heap
    with no kfree makes every per-fd allocation both leak and exhaust. The
    correct shape is a static bounded pool with explicit free-on-close, sized
    to the concurrency model (4 slots for single-foreground run-to-completion).
    `kmalloc` is a trap when there is no free.

  - A bounded static resource relocates the lifecycle problem; it doesn't
    remove it. The pool that fixed heap-exhaustion created a leak-on-abnormal-
    exit DoS — open four write-fds, exit without closing, the pool is dead
    until reboot. The cleanup half (`proc_reap` sweeping fds 3–31) is the
    obligation a static pool always implies. The problem just moved from the
    allocator to process teardown.

  - Audit the surface, not the calendar. The 1.41.5 security sweep ran before
    1.41.7 added the write-fd, so that surface went un-audited until 1.41.10
    explicitly went back for it. "We already swept this arc" silently excludes
    everything added after the sweep ran. A whole cut (1.41.10) existed only to
    audit a path a prior sweep predated.

  - Reject the unsound fix even when it's the audit's headline. At 1.41.11 the
    audit's primary proposed fix would have broken overwriting any existing
    file, because `fatfs_create` returns -1 on the normal name-collision case.
    A finding is a hypothesis; its remediation is a second hypothesis. Re-derive
    it against the real semantics before you ship it.

  - Iron-validation is per-arc and does not transfer. 1.33.1's indirect ext2
    write was iron-proven 2026-05-25 — and that says nothing about extent
    allocation (separate 1.37.x burn, 2026-05-28), jbd2 (separate 1.38.x burn,
    2026-05-28), or the 1.41.x FAT/exFAT write-fd (iron burn still pending).
    Each write path is a distinct on-disk-layout contract that earns its own
    burn. A default `mkfs.ext4` sets EXTENTS_FL — a different write path than
    the indirect one 1.33.x proved — which is the canonical example of why
    conflation poisons grounded answers.

  - 1.33.x is "ext2 indirect write, no journal," full stop. Crash-consistency
    came from ordered writes, not jbd2 — the 1.33.3 cut shipped an explicit
    no-journal story. The journal (1.38.x), extents (1.37.x), and generic
    VFS-write (1.39.x) are the base-CLOSE road, three later own-cycle arcs.
    Folding them into 1.33.x misstates which boundary the arc actually crossed.

  - Deliberate scope refusals are not omissions. The 1.41.3 group refuses
    cross-filesystem rename and returns -1 for FAT/exFAT `link` (no inodes, no
    hard links). Knowing what a syscall is built to refuse is as load-bearing
    as knowing what it does — those returns are the ABI's honesty about backend
    capability, not bugs to be filed.

[[entries]]
name = "exec_from_disk_the_four_in_one_burn"
description = "agnos 1.40.x exec-from-disk cycle — teaching the kernel to load a static ELF64 off the ext2 root and enter ring 3, the chain of iron-only faults it unmasked (gnoboot's ≥4 GB boot_info read, the scheduler dead-proc reset, the boot-stack rodata stomp, the mount-routing lie), the single 14013 burn that iron-validated four cuts at once, and the teardown closeout that shipped QEMU-only"
category = "cyrius"
---
EXEC IS THE HINGE

The storage trio gave the kernel somewhere to put files. The 1.40.x cycle
gave it a way to RUN them. From 1.40.0 (cycle-open 2026-05-28) to 1.40.14
(closeout 2026-05-31) — four days — AGNOS learned to read a static ELF64 off
the ext2 root, map each PT_LOAD segment into physical pages, and iretq into
ring 3 with a working SYSCALL path. `/bin/prog2` returns `run: exit 42`.
`/bin/argv Z` returns `run: exit 90`. The box prints `exec: selftest done`.

That sentence is the whole arc, and it took eleven cuts past the loader to
make it true on real silicon. Exec is the hinge between kernel and userland,
and it surfaces an entire latent class of QEMU-vs-iron divergence — code paths
the KTEST always bypassed, now exercised for the first time, each with its own
way of being wrong only on hardware. Here is the shape.

THE LOADER WAS THE EASY PART

The first four bites were almost boring. 1.40.1 added `vfs_read_file` — a
whole-file read past the old 4 KB memfile cap, FS-resolved across ext2/FAT/exFAT
(build 1,014,528 → 1,024,256 B). The finding that shaped everything downstream:
there is no large-contiguous allocator. `kmalloc` and `pmm_alloc` both cap at
one 4 KB page, so the load path can't buffer a binary — it has to STREAM.
1.40.2's `elf_load_from_file` reads each segment's bytes directly into physical
pages through the kernel identity map: no single buffer, no CR3 switch during
load.

Then 1.40.3 turned on ring 3 for the first time ever, and ten distinct first-run
bugs fell out of one bite. The core blocker was a single mis-encoded byte:
`mov cr3, r10` in the SYSCALL entry stub assembled as `44 0F 22 DA` (REX.R →
nonexistent cr11 → #UD) instead of `41 0F 22 DA` (REX.B → r10). Around it:
LSTAR programmed via NX-stack bytecode so wrmsr never ran; EFER.SCE not in
effect at first SYSCALL; a KPTI dual-CR3 mismatch; a hardcoded syscall kstack
overlapping the kernel image; SMAP blocking the kernel from reading the user
write() buffer (no STAC/CLAC); a TSS rsp0 read after the CR3 switch. Ten bugs,
+8 bytes of binary (1,033,296 → 1,033,304 B), and the entire ring-3 + SYSCALL
spine ran end-to-end in QEMU for the first time. exec-smoke 6/6.

By 1.40.8 the arc was declared iron-ready. The 1.40.5 setjmp/longjmp
`exec_and_wait` returned cleanly, the 1.40.6 multi-run fix handled two execs
per boot, argv/env passed through. The kernel had never been more confident.

THE A3 RESET — AND THE BUG THAT HID THE BUG

The 1408 burn (2026-05-30) passed 3 of 4 first try. Storage trio, ext2-write
suite, jbd2-clean, shtest, the ENOEXEC refusal — all green. Then A3, the
`/bin/prog2` ring-3 run, SPONTANEOUSLY RESET the box. No panic. No
`EXEC-DISK-OK`. QEMU `-cpu max` ran the identical binary 7/7.

The reset was itself a bug, and it had to be fixed before anything underneath
it could be diagnosed. `idt_init` had pointed all 256 vectors at a 2-byte bare
`iretq` stub — so any error-code fault during the ring-3 transition popped the
wrong frame, mis-returned, re-faulted, escalated #DF → #TF → silent CPU reset.
The fault erased its own cause. 1.40.9's `exc_handlers_init` installed real
handlers on the seven vectors a broken transition can raise (#UD/#DF/#TS/#NP/
#SS/#GP/#PF), each one stamping its vector to `CMOS[0x54]` plus magic `0xE5` to
`CMOS[0x55]` then `cli; hlt`. Pure port I/O — CR3-independent, no memory deref,
robust at fault time. On serial-less iron, CMOS port-I/O stamps are the
diagnostic of record.

The re-burn HALTED instead of resetting: `CMOS[0x54]=0x0E` = #PF, vector 14.
But the error code was `0x00` — not-present, read, SUPERVISOR, data. A
KERNEL-mode read of an unmapped address, not the user fault the textbook
predicted. CR2 low-24 came back `0x6190`, which the static audit proved was
mapped — so the real address had to be ≥4 GB, and `(k<<24)|0x6190` reads back
identically for every k. So the next burn stamped the full 48-bit CR2 plus the
faulting RIP: `CR2 = 0x000140006190`, `RIP(low32) = 0x00104fc8`. objdump put
that RIP inside `fb_fb_phys()`, on the instruction `load64(bi + 0x48)` — where
`bi` is the dereferenced `boot_info_ptr`.

ROOT CAUSE: gnoboot is a UEFI PE app the firmware loads at an arbitrary base,
and on RAM-rich Zen that base is ≥4 GB — `boot_info_ptr ≈ 0x140006148`, about
5 GB. The kernel read the boot_info struct IN PLACE at that address. That works
for the entire boot because Path C inherits UEFI's all-RAM identity map
(`pt_init` does `mov cr3, cr3` — a TLB flush of the live UEFI CR3, not a switch).
But `exec_and_wait` switches to the per-process CR3, which maps only 0–4 GB. The
program's first `write(1,…)` → console → `fb_fb_phys` → load64 at ≥4 GB →
unmapped → #PF. QEMU/OVMF loads gnoboot below 4 GB, so the bug cannot reproduce
there. It is the same CLASS as the 1.40.6 NVMe-BAR fault, for an address no
kernel page table ever held.

The fix: `boot_info_capture_rdi` memcpy's the 120-byte struct into a low
(<4 GB) kernel buffer `boot_info_copy[16]` at the top-level capture — while
UEFI's map is still live — and repoints `boot_info_ptr` at the copy. Every
later `fb_fb_phys`/`pitch`/`width`/`height` read is now CR3-independent. The
final re-burn (`1409_final_pass_test_reset_back`): EXEC-FROM-DISK PASSES ON
IRON. `/bin/prog2` exit 42, `/bin/argv` exit 90, `exec: selftest done`, rubric
A1–A7 green. The user tagged 1.40.9.

FIXING ONE IRON FAULT UNMASKS THE NEXT

The same photo's last line: the box reset right after `Activating scheduler...`
→ `dhcp: DISCOVER`. DHCP was innocent — the user said so ("nothing got changed
there") and was right. The now-WORKING exec selftest was the first thing in the
project's history to leave live process-table state before `sched_active=1`:
`proc_count ≥ 2`, `proc_current` on a dead (state=0) exec proc. The first timer
tick after activation — the DHCP `arch_wait` hlt — cleared
`do_context_switch`'s `proc_count < 2` early-return (the guard that had kept
DHCP working since 1.32.9), `sched_next` found no `state==1` proc, fell back to
`return 0` (a dead exec proc), `cr3_load`'d its stale per-process CR3 and iretq'd
into a ring-3 RIP under CS=0x08 → triple-fault → silent reset. QEMU never saw
it because SLIRP answers DISCOVER before a timer tick ever lands in the hlt.

A passing dispositive bar is not the end of the burn. The arc is a chain of
unmaskings, and you budget for it. 1.40.10's fix registered proc 0 = the kernel
main thread and proc 1 = a hlt idle thread (`kernel_idle_loop` + a module-scope
`var kernel_idle_stack[512]` = 4096 B), BOTH carrying boot CR3 `0x1000`, before
`sched_active=1`. All schedulable procs now share one CR3, so the
`new_cr3 != old_cr3` guard never fires, `cr3_load` is never invoked, and
preemption becomes pure register save/restore in one address space — a
kernel-threads model. Per-process-AS preemption is the future multi-threading
arc. QEMU could only validate no-regression here (no NIC, so the DHCP block is
skipped — exactly why it never caught the reset).

A RED SUCCESS MESSAGE THAT WASN'T A BROKEN FEATURE

1.40.12 caught a memory-safety bug that had been corrupting the kernel near the
2 MB line for the whole arc. `boot_shim.cyr` set `rsp = 0x200000` — fine when
the image was small, but the kernel image CROSSED 2 MB during 1.40.x, pushing
.rodata up to ~0x1faee8–0x1fff4c, immediately below the stack base. Every
push/call/spill wrote into the string-literal pool, and because the whole image
links as ONE RWE segment, those rodata writes succeeded silently.

It surfaced as a red exFAT-read `upcase-checksum` smoke row. The exFAT read path
was correct all along — its success literal `exfatu: upcase-checksum OK` just
happened to be one of the bytes the stack stomped. A success message being red
doesn't mean the feature is broken; it can mean its string got overwritten.
Caught precisely with a QEMU GDB hardware watchpoint on the corrupted byte —
writer was `push %rax` at `rsp=0x1ffbf8`. Fix: relocate the boot stack to
0x380000 (all three boot_shim sites), sitting in PMM-reserved region 1 between
the image top (~0x210000) and the fixed 0x3F0000 syscall kstack. Byte-size
unchanged (only immediate operands moved). sweep.sh went 6/7 → 7/7.

THE MOUNT-ROUTING LIE — QEMU PASSING FOR THE WRONG REASON

1.40.13 exposed the most insidious failure of the arc. On iron, raw `fatw:`
backend tests all PASSED but every shell-routed FAT verb FAILED with
`no such directory` / `no such parent` / `no such path` — strings that come
ONLY from the ext2 branch. Shell verbs routed by the `ext2_active` flag, not by
mount. On any box where ext2 is mounted — which is every real boot, because ext2
carries the exec arc's `/bin` — every verb took the ext2 branch and FAT/exFAT
were unreachable through the shell. The QEMU smokes hid it by booting with NO
ext2 partition, so every verb hit the secondary fallthrough. The smokes passed
for the wrong reason. This was the load-bearing routing half of the 1.39.x VFS
lift, deferred behind a `// non-goal §5` comment and wrongly papered over as
"functionally COMPLETE."

The fix: a `{prefix→backend}` mount registry plus a longest-prefix resolver —
ext2 at `/`, FAT at `/mnt/fat`, exFAT at `/mnt/exfat`, all live at once, every
verb resolving its absolute path to the owning backend. `fatfs_init` also went
two-pass to prefer a non-ESP FAT data partition over the boot ESP. Eight dead
`vfs_*_secondary` helpers came out: 117 → 109 functions, 1,052,824 → 1,050,200 B.

THE 14013 BURN — FOUR CUTS, ONE BOOT

On 2026-05-31 the `14013_final*` burn validated the WHOLE ARC at once. One
bug-capture boot (`14013_boot_cmd_fails`, the routing failure) then a
routing-fixed re-burn in three shots. pt1: ext2 at `/` (journal seq=4) plus
FAT32 mounted, FAT-through-shell while ext2 owns `/` — `SUBDIR-FAT-OK`. pt2/pt3:
a clean boot riding through `Activating scheduler...` → `dhcp: DISCOVER` →
`ACK ip=192.168.1.157` → `net: L2 OK` → `Launching kybernet...`, NO RESET. One
boot confirmed 1.40.9 exec, 1.40.10 scheduler, 1.40.12 boot-stack, and 1.40.13
routing simultaneously. Base maturity — FS-crash-safe plus exec-from-disk plus
scheduler-past-activation — closed on hardware. Test the real topology (ext2 at
`/` AND a secondary FS mounted), not the convenient one.

THE CLOSEOUT — AND THE LINE WE WON'T CROSS

1.40.14 is the part of this entry that did NOT boot on iron, and the honesty bar
demands the distinction. Resource reclaim is PART of exec, not an afterthought.
Without `proc_reap`/`proc_free_address_space`, the FOURTH sequential `run`
exhausts the 2 MB allocator — it serves only 6 usable regions (1–7, region 1
reserved), 2 consumed per run — a HARDER wall than the 16-slot proc-table limit.
The exec arc wasn't done when prog2 ran; it was done when the box could run
prog2 repeatedly. Teardown is the inverse of the loader.

`proc_free_address_space` walks the per-process PD and frees every user huge
page — identified by the U/S bit (present `0x01` AND user `0x04`), NOT a
divergence-from-kernel scan. The scan is unreliable because the first
`pmm_alloc_2mb` commonly returns region 2 = `0x400000`, which equals the code
segment's own identity vaddr — a physical coincidence that defeats divergence
detection. The semantic bit (it's a user page) survives the coincidence; the
heuristic doesn't. `proc_reap` marks the slot dead FIRST (scheduler-safe:
`sched_next` only selects state==1), detaches the stale CR3, frees the AS, LIFO
proc_count--. The closeout also removed the dead `u_pml4`/`u_pdpt`/`u_pd` KPTI
allocation — a silent 3-page-per-exec leak orphaned since the 1.40.3 KPTI
collapse — and AS construction now allocs exactly 3 reachable, reapable PT pages.

It validated QEMU-only: exec-smoke 7/7, sweep functional 6/6, check 11/11, and
two grep-visible reap-stability assertions (`reap: slot reclaim OK (pc stable)`
and `reap: 6x AS+page cycle, free stable OK`). EXEC-selftest build 1,054,936 B;
production build 1,050,392 B per the CHANGELOG. Its IRON RE-BURN was explicitly
PENDING, slated to ride the next Track-B FAT/exFAT burn. So as of 2026-05-31 the
pmm_alloc_2mb exhaustion FIX (which capped interactive `run` at ~3 invocations)
is QEMU-validated, NOT yet iron-proven. The 1.40.14 teardown has not booted on
hardware.

One footnote worth carrying: the exFAT-write "mkfs 1.3.2 format drift" that
shadowed several cuts was a MISDIAGNOSIS, corrected at 1.40.11. There was no
drift — the smoke had run against a leftover exec-iron build lacking
`EXFAT_WRITE_SELFTEST=1`, so AGNOS never wrote and `fsck.exfat -n` saw a pristine
image. A wrong-build guard now exits 2 with an actionable message. Don't
propagate it as a real backend bug.

LESSONS

  - Resource reclaim is PART of exec, not an afterthought. The FOURTH run
    exhausts the 2 MB allocator (6 usable regions, 2 per run) — harder than the
    16-slot proc-table limit — capping interactive `run` at ~3 invocations. The
    loader and its inverse ship together, or the feature only works a few times.

  - Identify user pages by the U/S bit (present 0x01 AND user 0x04), never by a
    divergence-from-kernel-map scan. The first pmm_alloc_2mb commonly returns
    region 2 = 0x400000 = the code segment's own identity vaddr; a
    physical-address coincidence defeats divergence detection. The semantic bit
    survives the coincidence; the heuristic doesn't.

  - A silent reset is itself a bug to fix before the underlying fault can be
    diagnosed. The bare-iretq IDT turned every transition fault into a
    triple-fault. Real handlers that CMOS-stamp the vector — then CR2, error
    code, the high CR2 bytes, RIP — converted an un-debuggable reboot into a
    precise localization: fb_fb_phys reading boot_info+0x48 at ≥4 GB. On
    serial-less iron, CMOS port-I/O stamps are the diagnostic of record.

  - Fixing one iron fault routinely UNMASKS the next. exec-from-disk passing
    (1.40.9) was the first thing to leave live process-table state before
    sched_active=1, exposing the latent scheduler dead-proc reset (1.40.10). A
    passing dispositive bar is not the end of the burn — budget for the chain.

  - A success message being red doesn't mean the feature is broken — its string
    literal may have been stomped. The exFAT-read path was correct; its
    `upcase-checksum OK` literal just sat in the top ~600 B of .rodata the boot
    stack overran once the image crossed 2 MB. A single RWE segment lets such
    corruption succeed silently. Suspect memory-safety near segment boundaries
    before suspecting the feature.

  - QEMU smokes can pass for the WRONG reason. The mount-routing bug was hidden
    because the smokes booted with no ext2 partition, so every verb hit the
    secondary fallthrough; on iron, ext2 owns `/` and every verb wrongly routed
    to ext2. Test the real topology, and beware a "functionally COMPLETE" label
    parked behind a `// non-goal` comment.

  - Three iron-only faults in one arc — the gnoboot ≥4 GB boot_info read, the
    scheduler dead-proc reset, the boot-stack rodata stomp — were all invisible
    in QEMU because OVMF loads gnoboot low, SLIRP answers DHCP fast, and the
    image hadn't crossed 2 MB. The 14013 burn validated all four fixes plus
    routing in a single boot. The teardown closeout (1.40.14) shipped
    QEMU-only; its iron re-burn was still pending. Iron-validated and
    software-complete are different claims — keep them apart.

[[entries]]
name = "the_shell_leaves_the_kernel"
description = "agnos 1.37.5 + 1.41.0-1.41.11 — extracting the console font to the kashi library, then walking the interactive shell out of ring 0 into a userland agnsh while a recovery REPL stays behind: a kernel-slimming arc that GREW the binary first, an audit that aged out from under a new write path, and a sovereign-syscall boundary that no cross-repo gate could shortcut"
category = "cyrius"
---
THE SHELL LEAVES THE KERNEL

The shortest description of this arc is a boundary that became permanent: the interactive shell stopped living in ring 0. PID 1 kybernet now execs a userland `/bin/agnsh` in ring 3 from the ext2 root, and the in-kernel shell shrinks to a recovery REPL — a fallback, not the home. That boundary is locked as a contract at agnos 1.41.9 and hardened through 1.41.11. Before any of it could happen, a smaller arc had to land first: the console font had to leave the kernel too, extracted at 1.37.5 into the `kashi` library and vendored back through a build-time prepend.

Two slimming moves, two surprises. The first slimming move GREW the binary. The second exposed an audit that had already aged out from under a path that didn't exist yet. And the whole shell-separation half is SOFTWARE-COMPLETE and QEMU-green — it has not booted on iron. The iron burn is staged at 1.41.11 and pending on archaemenid; do not read this entry as proof the userland shell ran on real hardware. The only iron-validated thing underneath it is the 1.40.x exec-from-disk foundation (burned 2026-05-31, `14013_final*`), which is exactly why the arc was viable at all.

THE FONT LEAVES FIRST — AND THE KERNEL GROWS

Console-font work was slated for the 1.40.x slot. The user pulled it forward to the close of the 1.37.x arc (2026-05-27) so a PARALLEL agent could own the new repo: agnos sessions touch only the extraction-and-consumption boundary, never `kashi` internals. kashi 0.1.0 was set up by extracting agnos's own glyph tables byte-for-byte out of `kernel/arch/x86_64/fb_console.cyr` — the 8x16 VGA core from HEAD, the 8x8 CGA core recovered from git `75914e9^` — into a freestanding, zero-dependency `src/font_data.cyr`. The audit recorded 0 mismatches. Glyph rendering after extraction is byte-identical to 1.37.4 by construction.

The hand-off landed at agnos 1.37.5 (2026-05-28). `fb_console.cyr` retired its inline glyph machinery: `var fb_font[1536]` (the 96-glyph BSS), the `fset16` packing helper (24 lines), and a 96-line literal-load block that called `fset16(0x20..0x7F)` glyph by glyph. All of it collapsed to one `kashi_font_init()` call plus a `kashi_glyph_ptr(KASHI_FONT_VGA_8X16, ch)` lookup with a null guard. `cyrius.cyml` gained `[deps.kashi]`. The vendored core is 763 lines / 43,052 bytes.

And the production build went from 843,776 to 945,360 bytes — it added 101,584 bytes. A move whose entire purpose was to shed inline font tables made the kernel bigger. The reason is honest and worth internalizing: the extracted library is more general than what agnos consumed. kashi vendors the full CP437 range — 224 glyphs, 0x20–0xFF — for VGA 8x16 AND CGA 8x8, plus a derived `KASHI_FONT_VGA_9X16` variant and accessors, against agnos's prior 96-glyph (0x20–0x7F) single-font slice. Cyrius dead-code elimination is off by default; `CYRIUS_DCE=1` flags 141 unreachable functions / 48,203 bytes, roughly half the delta. DCE was left off deliberately to keep build behavior identical across the swap.

The real byte win came later, at the shell shrink — but the lesson here is that "slimming" is measured at the OWNERSHIP boundary first, not the byte count. `fb_console.cyr` stopped owning glyph tables. That was the win, even as the number went the wrong way.

THE PREPEND FOOTGUN

Extracting the font created a build-time coupling that every kernel-build entry point now has to honor. `kashi`'s font core isn't pulled through the language's dep resolver for the kernel build — it's prepended, literally `cat ../kashi/src/font_data.cyr` ahead of `cyrius build --no-deps`, so the freestanding glyph symbols are in scope when `fb_console.cyr` references `kashi_font_init`, `kashi_glyph_ptr`, and `KASHI_FONT_VGA_8X16`. 1.37.5 mirrored that prepend into `build.sh` and `test.sh`. The pin sits at `KASHI_REF=1.0.0` — kashi's v1 API freeze, dated the same day as the cut, 2026-05-28 (the 1.37.5 note names kashi 0.6.0 as the version actually vendored at cut-time; kashi reached 1.0.0 that day).

`scripts/bench.sh` was never updated. Confirmed by direct code inspection at the current head (agnos VERSION=1.41.11): `bench.sh` has zero `kashi` / `font_data` / `KASHI` references and still invokes `cyrius build -D ARCH_X86_64 agnos.cyr` with no prepend, while `fb_console.cyr` calls symbols defined ONLY in kashi's `font_data.cyr`. That path emits undefined symbols when it runs. It is a real, latent break.

It needs to be flagged precisely, because nothing logged it: no CHANGELOG, state.md, or iron-log entry records `bench.sh` failing. "It silently broke at 1.37.5" is a code-grounded inference, not an attested incident — and as of 1.41.11 the omission is unfixed. Whether `bench.sh` has even been RUN since 1.37.5 is unknown; the break may be purely latent. Either way the shape of the lesson is fixed: a build-time vendoring mechanism is a cross-cutting invariant. Enumerate every entry point and patch each one, or add a guard. A missed prepend is invisible until that one path runs.

THE SHELL-SEPARATION ARC OPENS

1.41.0 (2026-05-31) was staging only, no kernel code: an inventory of the 35 in-kernel shell verbs against the 28-entry syscall table, and surfacing the gating prerequisite — `CYRIUS_TARGET_AGNOS`, a cyrius-side deliverable. The cycle-open bumped 1.40.14 → 1.41.0; production byte-behavior was unchanged but for banner strings. The dependency framing here is the whole arc in miniature: agnos owned every kernel bite, but `agnsh` literally could not run until cyrius shipped an agnos-target stdlib peer. The correct framing was "add a Cyrius target," NOT "make agnos answer Linux syscalls" — the latter would have collapsed the sovereign 28-syscall surface.

1.41.1 wired the first interactive ring-3 syscall: `read(fd=0)` now blocks on the keyboard and returns typed chars to a userland process (ABI decision O1, RAW). Build 1,050,824 B. No automated test is possible — a seeded stdin test hangs headless QEMU — so this bite's only validation is an iron burn, still pending. (1.41.2 was a PARALLEL boot_info side-bite — canary + ACPI RSDP fallback, the agnos half of gnoboot v0.5.0 — not shell separation; it shifted the bite numbering down one.)

1.41.3 made the filesystem real over the syscall ABI: 9 syscalls wired to the 1.40.13 mount-routed VFS against the frozen `agnos-userland-abi.md` — `open(7)` re-routed with flags; `mkdir(9)`, `rmdir(10)`, `sync(12)` made real; new `getdents(29)`, `unlink(30)`, `rename(31)`, `link(32)`, `stat(33)`; plus the a4=r10 ABI extension (decision O2). `chdir`/`getcwd` were deliberately NOT made syscalls — CWD is userland-owned. fssys: ALL PASS, sweep 7/7.

THE #UD AT THE PROMPT, AND THE CROSS-REPO GATE

1.41.4 (2026-06-03) was first boot-to-agnsh-on-disk: PID 1 kybernet execs `/bin/agnsh` — the agnos-target build of agnoshi, ~5 K LOC / 295 KB static — in ring 3 from the ext2 root, with the in-kernel `shell()` demoted to a fallback. It was blocked, hard, on a cross-repo gate. `agnsh` is OS-agnostic and had only ever built against the Linux syscall ABI, because that was the only Cyrius target available. On AGNOS it died at startup with a #UD — illegal instruction — and never reached its prompt. The specific crash was `args_init()` with no init-stack capture in the cyrius agnos-stdlib peer; `lib/io.cyr` also carried an agnos file-op ABI miscompile, and there was no real exec.

None of that was an agnos fix. It was driven entirely by the cyrius agent: cyrius 6.0.55 added `args_agnos.cyr` plus the init-stack capture (closing the `args_init` #UD) and fixed the `io.cyr` miscompile; 6.0.56 added `process_agnos.cyr`, giving a real `sys_spawn`-based exec. agnos moved its toolchain pin 6.0.14 → 6.0.56 and rebuilt byte-clean on the new codegen (1,061,944 B at the rebuild note). Then `agnsh` reached its ring-3 prompt with no #UD and no emergency fallback — QEMU agnsh-smoke PASS ×3, deterministic. Iron pending. The transferable point: a cross-repo gating prerequisite can stall an OS arc even when every line of the OS-side code is done. Sequence both halves of an ABI together, and respect the sovereign boundary while you do it.

PUT AN UNTRUSTED CALLER ON THE FAR SIDE AND THE FD TABLE BECOMES A WEAPON

Once a real userland shell sat on the far side of the syscall boundary, the boundary became an attack surface. 1.41.5 ran a 6-dimension multi-agent adversarial audit over the now-live ring-3→ring-0 ingress: 26 findings (10 high / 3 medium / 13 low, 0 refuted), 15 fixed this cut — all 10 high, plus 2 medium and 3 low.

The headline was fd type-confusion. `epoll_ctl`, `epoll_wait`, and `timerfd_settime` never checked the fd's ktag. A ring-3 caller could pass any other fd type whose `payload[2]` is a kernel heap pointer — a pipe or memfile fd — or a small integer, like an ext2 fd's inode number; the handler's `store64`/`load64` then wrote or read arbitrary kernel memory. The fix was a VFS_* tag check per handler, mirroring the `getdents` precedent rather than reinventing it, plus a bound on the watched fd so it can't index `vfs_table` out of range. The same cut added the 1 GB user-VA ceiling in `is_user_range`/`is_user_ptr`, capped ext2 basename overflow at 255, validated the spawn ELF buffer and `p_vaddr` bound, capped an mmap length-overflow, and guarded a FAT-chain cycle. Type-confusion across an fd table IS an arbitrary read/write primitive the moment untrusted callers reach it — a tag check per handler, plus a bound on any fd used as an index, is the floor.

1.41.6 (2026-06-04) took the deferred exec-hardening half: a new `SYSCALL_HARDEN_SELFTEST` safety net (shsys: ALL PASS — first regression coverage for epoll/timerfd/signalfd), and the #11 ELF-leak fix, where `elf_load`/`elf_load_from_file` now validate every PT_LOAD in a pre-pass BEFORE allocating, so a malformed ELF is rejected with zero allocations to leak. It also deduped a shared `sc_path_ok` preamble (#22) and renumbered the FS syscall group (#21). One audit proposal was REJECTED on purpose: #23, a single-tail canary rewrite, would have meant rewriting ~25 early-returns in the security-critical dispatcher for a non-vuln cosmetic. A finding is a question, not a patch.

THE WRITE PATH THE SWEEP PREDATED

1.41.7 (2026-06-04) surfaced a gap while planning the shell-shrink: `vfs_write` was ext2/pipe/device-only, so FAT/exFAT content-write was reachable ONLY through the in-kernel shell's `echo>` (`vfs_write_secondary`). That couldn't survive once the in-kernel shell was demoted. So 1.41.7 added a new VFS_SEC_WFILE write-fd: `open(7)` with write access on a FAT/exFAT mount buffers content and flushes the whole file on close, backed by a STATIC 4-slot pool freed on close — not `kmalloc`, because the alloc-only heap leaks. A new syscall-driven `syswr` selftest covered FAT and exFAT. Known limit: a 4 KB whole-file cap per fd, no append, no streaming.

This is the trap that aged out from under the audit. The 1.41.5 ingress sweep had run BEFORE 1.41.7 existed, so the entire open-routing / write / flush / pool surface was never swept. A security audit is DATED; anything landed after it is unaudited until re-swept. The 1.41.10 arc-close pass exists precisely to "audit the path the sweep predated," and it found real teeth: a 3-dimension adversarial audit, 4 real findings (3 medium / 1 low, 0 refuted), 3 fixed. The worst — a write-open of a directory PATH on a FAT/exFAT mount flushed through the backend and freed the directory's cluster chain, on-disk filesystem corruption; both backends now refuse to overwrite a directory via an attr-0x10 guard. Plus the 4-slot pool leaking on process exit (a ring-3 DoS), fixed by an fd-reclaim sweep in `proc_reap` that closes fds 3-31 with an idempotent `vfs_close`; and `vfs_sec_wfile_write` returning 0 at the 4 KB cap, which spun a conforming write loop forever — now an error.

MIGRATE, THEN DELETE

The shell-shrink itself was done in the safe order. The FAT/exFAT/ext2 write selftests had driven the in-kernel shell's write VERBS through `sh_exec("touch …")`. 1.41.8 re-pointed those tests at SYSCALLS — the same path `agnsh` uses — so the verbs became undriven. Only then, at 1.41.9, were they deleted. Never delete a surface a green test still exercises; move the test to the surface that survives first.

1.41.9 is where the boundary locked. The in-kernel shell shed its non-recovery verbs — `touch`, `echo>` redirect, `mkdir`, `rmdir`, `ln`, `bench` (+`bench_report`), `ps`, `free`, `jbd2`, and the now-dead `sh_write_selftest`. `shell.cyr` went 1,149 → 813 LOC (−336); the production kernel went 1,084,312 → 1,070,288 B — the real −14,024-byte (~−14 KB) slim, the one the font extraction never delivered. The deletion was done by a subagent from the 1.41.8 spec and independently re-verified: grep confirmed zero dangling references, all recovery verbs present, clean build.

What stayed is the point. The recovery REPL keeps `help`/`cd`/`pwd`/`ls`/`cat`/`run`/`mv`/`rm`/`sync`/`reboot` and the read-only management verbs (`uptime`, `lspci`, `cpus`, `net`, `parts`, and the rest); `echo` shrinks to a bare print. The in-kernel shell is deliberately KEPT as the boot fallback for when `/bin/agnsh` is absent or corrupt — slimming the kernel does not mean removing the emergency path, it means demoting it to recovery-only. (Honesty footnote: the CHANGELOG's "recovery REPL" framing is right — every WRITE/management verb is gone — but the kept set is broad. "Minimal" would overstate it; the shrunk shell still carries a substantial read-only verb list.)

CLEAN, AND STAGED FOR IRON

1.41.10 closed the audit gap above. 1.41.11 is clean-and-iron-prep — the arc is SOFTWARE-COMPLETE. It took only the residual 1.41.10 low fix: `vfs_close` now surfaces the write-fd flush rc instead of swallowing it, so a failed FAT/exFAT backend write reports the error to `close()`. The audit's PRIMARY proposed fix for that finding was REJECTED — again — because it was unsound: it would have broken overwrite, since `fatfs_create` returns -1 on the normal name-collision. Only the sound secondary fix was taken. Twice in this arc the audit's headline remedy had to be turned down (the 1.41.6 canary rewrite and this one); both times the proposal failed to preserve documented behavior. Verify the remedy, not just the finding. Build moved 1,070,288 → 1,070,720 B (+432).

Then the iron tracker was staged: `#tracker-141x-cycle`, with an A1–A4 dispositive rubric — boot-to-agnsh in ring 3; recovery-shell fallback; FAT/exFAT write fsck-clean; no exec/storage/net regression. All of QEMU is green: agnsh-smoke PASS ×3, sweep 7/7, fssys ALL PASS, shsys ALL PASS, check.sh 11/11. None of it has booted on archaemenid. As of 2026-06-04 there are no fresh top-level iron photos in git status, and the burn is user-driven and pending. The 1.40.x exec-from-disk + VFS-routing foundation this whole arc rides on IS iron-validated (2026-05-31), and that foundation — exited processes finally reclaiming their address space via `proc_reap`, after 1.40.x had been exhausting `pmm_alloc_2mb` on the 4th sequential `run` — is exactly the "why now" that made a long-lived ring-3 `agnsh` viable. But the shell-separation arc itself is a QEMU verdict awaiting an iron verdict. Do not claim agnsh ran on real hardware.

LESSONS

  - Factoring a vendored dependency into the source through a build-time mechanism — a prepend ahead of `cyrius build --no-deps`, not the language's dep resolver — makes that mechanism a cross-cutting invariant. 1.37.5 mirrored the kashi font prepend into `build.sh` and `test.sh` but not `bench.sh`; `bench.sh` still has zero kashi references at 1.41.11 and emits undefined symbols (`KASHI_FONT_VGA_8X16`, `kashi_glyph_ptr`, `kashi_font_init`) when it runs. A missed prepend is invisible until that path runs. Enumerate and patch every build entry point, or add a guard. (This one is a code-grounded inference — no source logs it as a discovered incident, and it is unfixed.)

  - A "kernel-slimming" move can legitimately GROW the binary first. 1.37.5 ADDED +101,584 B while shedding the inline font tables, because the extracted library is more general (full CP437 × two faces + a derived variant) than what agnos consumed, and DCE was left off to keep behavior identical. Measure slimming at the SOURCE/ownership boundary — `fb_console.cyr` stops owning glyph tables — not always at the byte count. The byte win came later: −14 KB at the shell shrink (1.41.9).

  - Migrate-then-delete is the safe order for removing a subsystem that tests depend on. The write selftests drove the in-kernel shell's verbs via `sh_exec("touch …")`; 1.41.8 re-pointed them at syscalls (the surface that survives), so 1.41.9 could delete the verbs with zero coverage loss, verified by a subagent plus an independent grep for dangling refs. Never delete a surface a green test still exercises.

  - A security audit is dated. Any privileged feature landed after the sweep is unaudited until re-swept. The 1.41.5 ingress audit predated the 1.41.7 VFS_SEC_WFILE write-fd, which then harbored a directory-overwrite FS-corruption bug, a pool-leak DoS, and an infinite-spin-at-cap bug — all caught only by the explicit 1.41.10 "audit the path the sweep predated" pass. Track what the last sweep did NOT cover.

  - Type-confusion across an fd table is an arbitrary-read/write primitive the moment untrusted callers reach the syscall boundary. `epoll_ctl`/`epoll_wait`/`timerfd_settime` trusted `payload` without checking the ktag; a ring-3 caller could pass a pipe/memfile fd (kernel heap ptr) or an ext2 fd (inode number) and turn `store64`/`load64` into kernel write/read. Fix: a tag check per handler plus a bound on any fd used as a table index — mirror the established precedent (`getdents`), don't reinvent it per call site.

  - Lock the boundary as a PERMANENT contract and keep the kernel side as a non-collapsing fallback. The shell-separation payoff is the permanent kernel↔userland shell boundary: kernel shell = recovery only, `agnsh` = full interactive. The in-kernel REPL is deliberately kept as the boot fallback for when `/bin/agnsh` is absent or corrupt (the A2 rubric item burns exactly that). Demote the emergency path; don't delete it.

  - Reject the audit's proposed fix when it isn't behavior-sound, and document why. Twice this arc the adversarial audit's PRIMARY remedy was turned down — 1.41.6 #23 (a single-tail canary rewrite touching ~25 early-returns in the security-critical dispatcher for a non-vuln cosmetic) and 1.41.11 #4 (the proposed fix would break overwrite, because `fatfs_create` returns -1 on the normal name-collision). Only the sound secondary fixes were taken. A finding is a question, not a patch; verify the remedy preserves documented behavior before applying it.

  - A cross-repo gating prerequisite can stall an OS arc even when every line of OS-side code is done. The 1.41.x arc was gated on a CYRIUS-side deliverable (`CYRIUS_TARGET_AGNOS` — an agnos-target stdlib peer emitting agnos syscall numbers). agnos owned the kernel bites — stdin, FS syscalls, exec — but `agnsh` couldn't run until cyrius 6.0.55/6.0.56 landed `args`/`io`/`process` for the agnos target (the pin moved 6.0.14 → 6.0.56). The correct framing was "add a Cyrius target," NOT "make agnos answer Linux syscalls," which would have broken the sovereign 28-syscall surface. Sequence both halves of an ABI together, and respect the sovereign boundary.

  - And the honesty discipline that outlasts the arc: the entire 1.41.x shell-separation half is QEMU-green and software-complete — agnsh-smoke PASS ×3, sweep 7/7, fssys/shsys ALL PASS, check.sh 11/11 — and has NOT booted on iron. The iron burn is staged at 1.41.11 with an A1–A4 rubric, pending, user-driven on archaemenid. Only the 1.40.x exec foundation beneath it is iron-validated (2026-05-31). A QEMU verdict is a hypothesis until iron answers.
